1. d4 {Welcome to our course, "QGA 3.e4 for White," part of the "1.d4 According to Dreev" series!} d5 2. c4 dxc4 {The Queen’s Gambit Accepted (QGA) is one of Black’s most classical and principled responses to 1.d4. By capturing the c4-pawn early, Black aims for quick development and central control—but White has many ways to challenge this setup.} 3. e4 {In this course, we advocate the ambitious 3.e4!, which immediately seizes space in the center and sets the tone for active, dynamic play. Compared to the more modest 3.Nf3 or 3.e3, this move puts maximum pressure on Black from the very beginning. It’s a powerful weapon that can catch unprepared opponents off guard—and even against well-prepared ones, it leads to interesting positions with the initiative that offer excellent winning chances.} e5 {Black's most direct continuation—this will be analyzed in detail in the first part of the course.} (3... Nf6 {An ambitious move—rather than playing for equality, Black simply wants to get a game.} 4. e5 Nd5 5. Bxc4 {Now, Black has three important continuations:} Nb6 {The main line will be analyzed in Chapter 6. Here, we need to understand whether to play 6.Bb3 or 6.Bd3, as this choice makes a huge difference.} (5... Nc6 {the "Carlsen line", and we will analyze it in Chapter 7.}) (5... Bf5 {the "Jobava line", and we will analyze it in Chapter 8.})) (3... Nc6 {This line was often played in the past, but nowadays it’s quite rare. Why? Because White obtains a strategically more interesting position. We will analyze this move in Chapters 9 and 10.}) (3... b5 {We have named this the "Engine's line" because Black can survive here only by playing a long sequence of engine-only moves. However, we must know how to pose practical problems even against well-prepared opponents—this is why we will study this line in Chapter 11.}) (3... e6 {Black's less common options on move 3, such as 3...e6 and 3...c5, will be covered in Chapter 12. While these lines are not as popular as the main continuations, they contain important nuances that every player should be aware of.}) 4. Nf3 exd4 (4... Nf6 {GM Dominguez loved to play this line, but we have almost refuted it. We say almost because in the final position—where the evaluation is already +1.20 or more—we're still not sure whether Black can survive with precise engine moves or not.}) (4... Bb4+ {Favorite move of GM Vachier Lagrave.} 5. Nc3 {We will analyze this position in Chapter 2 because here Black can play} exd4 {Classical way.} (5... Nf6 $5 {engine's direct continuation.})) 5. Bxc4 Nc6 (5... Bb4+ {The biggest expert in this line is GM Rublevsky, and I’ve played many games against him in this variation. We will analyze it in Chapter 3.}) 6. O-O Be6 {Black's classical continuation. In Chapter 5, I will explain my point of view after all three of White’s main moves.} (6... Nf6 {GM Bauer loved to play this line, and we will try to refute it in Chapter 4.}) (6... Bc5 {another tricky move, if we just continue with} 7. Ng5 {which is White's most common continuation, after} Nh6 8. Nxf7 Nxf7 9. Bxf7+ Kxf7 10. Qh5+ g6 11. Qxc5 Re8 $1 $13 {The position is not so clear. So how should we continue against 6...Bc5? We will discuss it in Chapter 4.}) 7. Nbd2 $5 {Modern way.} (7. Bb5 {Concrete way.}) (7. Bxe6 {Classical way.}) *

