1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 e5 (3... Nf6 {Second most common continuation.} 4. e5 Nd5 5. Bxc4 Nb6 {The main line by far.} (5... Nc6 {[%csl Gb5,Rc6][%cal Yd5b6,Gc4b5] The drawback of this move is that once Black will play Nb6, White will have Bb5 options.} 6. Nc3 Nb6 7. Bb5 Bd7 8. Nge2 $5 {I like this more, and it was played also by the Ex-World Champion, Ding Liren.} e6 9. a3 $14 {[%csl Ga3][%cal Rc6b4,Rf8b4,Ge1g1] This is a key positional move against the 3...Nf6 variation.}) 6. Bb3 {My recommendation.} Nc6 (6... Bf5 {Logical move, but now we can play} 7. Nf3 {[%csl Gf3][%cal Rf5g4] because Bg4 would cost an entire tempo, for example:} e6 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. O-O Be7 10. a3 $14 {[%csl Ga3] again this very useful move is important.}) 7. Be3 $5 {Useful waiting move: we wait for Bf5 before playing Nf3.} ({If we now play} 7. Nf3 {then Black can continue with} Bg4 $11 {[%csl Gg4]}) 7... Bf5 8. Nc3 e6 9. a3 $1 {[%csl Ga3][%cal Rc6b4,Rf8b4] No need to repeat that this move is always useful for us :).} Qd7 {[%csl Gd7][%cal Gc6a5]} 10. Nf3 O-O-O 11. Qe2 $1 {[%csl Gc4,Rd1,Ge2][%cal Rc6a5] Prophylaxis move, to remove the queen from the d-file and also guard the c4 square.} Kb8 12. O-O Bg4 {Logical idea, but White should be better.} 13. h3 $5 {Good inclusion.} Bh5 14. Rfd1 $14 {[%cal Gc3e4,Ga1c1] Rac1-Ne4 next.}) (3... Nc6 {Black challenges our center by fighting for the d4 square (or e5 square in case of d5). This variation has a very similar spirit to the Chigorin.} 4. Nf3 Bg4 {This is Black's most common continuation.} 5. d5 Ne5 6. Bf4 {We force Ng6.} Ng6 7. Be3 (7. Bg3 $6 e5 $13 {[%csl Rg3] Our bishop is misplaced on g3.}) 7... e5 8. Bxc4 Nf6 (8... a6 $6 {Black sometimes starts with a6 if he wants to avoid Bb5+, but this is anyway not our idea, and by playing a6, Black wasted an important tempo.} 9. h3 $1 Bd7 10. d6 $1 {We can concretely punish Black for his 8...a6.} Bxd6 11. Qd5 Qe7 12. Qxb7 $16) 9. Nc3 a6 {by far, Black's most popular continuation. I don't know why so many players are scared of Bb5+.} 10. O-O Bd6 11. h3 {We immediately force Black's bishop to retreat.} Bd7 12. a4 $1 O-O 13. a5 $1 $146 {[%cal Gf1e1,Gc4f1,Gf3d2] We take space on the queenside, and we have a lot of long-term plans.}) (3... b5 {A lot of years ago, it was considered a dubious move, but nowadays, with the improvement of new engines the opinion has changed.} 4. a4 c6 5. axb5 cxb5 6. Nc3 {Black has 2 main options now:} a6 {Most common move, but this line is in a bit of crisis now.} (6... Qb6 $5 {This line will soon overtake the move 6...a6 in popularity, the reason is clear: Black plays for 3 results.} 7. Be3 $5 {My recommendation, it's a rare line (only 18 games compared to 80 in the main line), so we have chances to surprise our opponents.} e6 8. Nh3 $5 {[%csl Gf2,Gh3][%cal Gf2f3] Good development, maybe sometimes in the future we will need to play f2-f3 (which wouldn't be possible with a knight on f3).} Nf6 9. Be2 Bb4 {The critical move, only 3 games exist here.} 10. Bf3 O-O {was played in 2 high level games.} 11. Ng5 $5 h6 12. h4 $1 $36 {Very interesting idea, played in both games. If Black is not prepared, they can resign in a few moves.}) 7. Nxb5 axb5 8. Rxa8 Bb7 9. Ra1 e6 $1 {[%cal Rb2b3,Gf8b4] Only move for Black, in order to have Bb4+ in case of b3.} (9... Bxe4 $2 {It's a mistake to take the pawn immediately.} 10. f3 $1 Bd5 {Logical move.} 11. b3 $1 $16 {[%csl Rc4] And Black is not in time to defend the pawn in a satisfactory way.}) 10. Ne2 $5 {[%cal Ge2c3] The safest move, plan is simple: to meet Bxe4 with Nc3.} (10. f3 {The main move, but after} f5 $1 $132 {Black gets some kind of counterplay.}) 10... Bxe4 11. Nc3 Bb4 $1 {The best move.} 12. Be2 Nf6 13. O-O Bxc3 14. bxc3 $36 {Black needs to play like an engine to defend.}) 4. Nf3 {Black's main moves are 4...Bb4+ (1000 games) and 4...exd4 (5000 games).} exd4 (4... Bb4+ 5. Nc3 exd4 {Historical way.} (5... Nf6 $5 {Engine way.} 6. Nxe5 $5 {My recommendation, I think it's more interesting than 6.Bxc4, Black has a lot of safety there.} b5 $1 {Black's idea.} 7. Be2 $5 {Much more rare than the main 7.f3.} Nxe4 {Most logical move, played by Dominguez.} 8. O-O Bxc3 $1 {The best move, played by Dominguez.} 9. bxc3 Nxc3 10. Qc2 Nxe2+ 11. Qxe2 O-O 12. Ba3 $36 {[%csl Ra8,Rf7][%cal Rf8e8,Ge2f3] White will win an exchange, because Re8 is impossible, because of Qf3, but it's not all.}) 6. Nxd4 Ne7 {[%cal Gb8c6] Classical line, Black is preparing Nbc6.} (6... Nd7 {[%cal Gg8f6,Rd1a4] Popular line, Black wants to develop the knight to a natural square on f6, but first without allowing Qa4+ of course.} 7. Bxc4 Ngf6 8. f3 O-O 9. Be2 {Very good prophylactic move.} (9. O-O Qe7 $5 {[%cal Re7c5] is one extra option.}) 9... Ne5 (9... Qe7 $6 {runs under tempo.} 10. Nf5 $1 $14 {One big difference on why we start with 9.Be2.}) 10. O-O $14 {[%csl Ge4,Gf3,Rf6]}) 7. Bf4 $5 {This is my main recommendation, it's a positional line, without risk. For the moment, it stops Nb6.} O-O {Logical, the only move that makes sense.} (7... Nbc6 $6 {is met with} 8. Ndb5 $14 {[%csl Rc7] c7 is impossible to defend.}) 8. Bxc4 Nbc6 9. Nde2 $5 $146 {Novelty, interesting idea.} (9. Ndb5 $6 $146 {Novelty, but unfortunately, not so inspiring for White.} Ng6 $1 10. Bxc7 Qg5 11. O-O a6 $13 {Black has full compensation, and it could be a bit risky for White.}) 9... Qxd1+ {Black goes for the endgame:} 10. Rxd1 $14) 5. Bxc4 Nc6 (5... Bb4+ {This is GM Rublevsky's favorite line. I have faced him multiple times in this variation, gaining valuable insights from our games.} 6. Nbd2 {[%csl Gd2] More interesting than 6.Bd2, in my opinion.} Nc6 7. O-O Nf6 8. e5 Nd5 9. Nb3 Nb6 {Black's main continuation by far.} (9... O-O $2 {bad move order:} 10. Nbxd4 Nb6 11. Nxc6 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 bxc6 13. Bb3 $16 {[%csl Ra7,Rc6,Rc7][%cal Gb3c2,Gc2e4] Maybe Bc2-Be4 next, and White has a better endgame due to Black's bad queenside pawn structure.}) (9... Be7 {Rare sideline, and White has a lot of ideas here.} 10. Nbxd4 {Simple way.} Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Nb6 12. Bb3 Qxd4 (12... O-O $2 13. Qe4 $16 {[%csl Ge4]}) 13. Nxd4 O-O 14. e6 fxe6 15. Nxe6 Bxe6 16. Bxe6+ $14 {Not too much, but White is slightly better thanks to the two bishops.}) 10. Bg5 Be7 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Bb5 Bd7 {And now, White has two interesting directions.} (12... O-O $6 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. Rc1 $14 {Should be at least slightly better for White.}) 13. Bxc6 {White's main continuation, and I have also played it many times.} Bxc6 14. Nfxd4 Bd5 {If not Bd5, we can take on c6 and play with a better pawn structure.} 15. Qg4 O-O {Black's most common continuation, but here we have three possible directions, and each of them is interesting.} (15... h5 $1 {is Black's best reaction, but it was played only three times!} 16. Qh3 $1 {The only interesting move—I found it back in 2003!}) 16. f4 {[%cal Gd4f5] most concrete way: our idea is Nf5.} (16. Rfe1 {positional way.}) (16. Rae1 $5 $146 {new way.})) 6. O-O Be6 7. Nbd2 $5 {My most recent try, and I believe that it's the most interesting one.} Qf6 {Black's most common continuation and probably the best.} (7... Bd6 {Not a bad line, but White has a lot of ideas here.} 8. Bxe6 fxe6 9. Nc4 {[%csl Gc4]}) ({If Black just plays a normal developing move like} 7... Nf6 {then after} 8. Qb3 $1 {White can be better, for example:} Qd7 $1 9. Qxb7 Rb8 10. Qa6) 8. Qa4 {[%csl Ca4] White's best chance, in my opinion.} O-O-O $1 {only good move.} (8... Bc5 $2 {Big mistake played in the game L'Ami-Stevic, 2022.} 9. b4 $1 $146) 9. Rd1 $5 $146 {This is my recommendation. While 9.b4 can lead to an immediate win, if your opponent is well-prepared, the game will end in a forced draw. That's why we need a secondary option—to keep the game alive and play chess (if the opponent is not a computer! )} (9. b4 {Another very good try: Black will need to play a lot of only moves to survive.}) *

