{[%evp 0,29,19,13,15,3,13,11,24,31,31,17,28,-6,-27,-26,-32,-69,-94,-70,-62,-72,-62,-39,-39,-45,-46,2,2,89,19,4]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 e5 4. Nf3 {Black's main moves are 4...Bb4+ (1000 games) and 4...exd4 (5000 games).} Nf6 {GM Dominguez has often played this move. Although 4...Nf6 doesn't objectively equalize, it can be a tricky continuation if White is not well prepared against it.} (4... Bg4 $2 {Was played more than 100 times, but it is basically losing:} 5. Bxc4 {Black tried different moves, but the engine's evaluation is already +2,00.} exd4 (5... Bxf3 6. Qxf3 Qf6 7. Qb3 $1 b6 8. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3d5]} c6 9. dxe5 $18) 6. Qb3 Qe7 7. Nxd4 Qb4+ 8. Nc3 Qxb3 9. axb3 c6 10. O-O $18 {White has a decisive development advantage.}) 5. Bxc4 $1 {White's best, and the only move to fight for an advantage.} Nxe4 {Looks dangerous for Black, but White should know exactly what to do.} (5... Bb4+ {Is more solid than 5...Nxe4, but it's not in the spirit of 4...Nf6.} 6. Bd2 Bxd2+ 7. Nbxd2 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd2e4] We defend the pawn on e4.} exd4 8. e5 $1 {Very important to play it before including 00-00. Why? Because Black will have the f7 pawn problem.} (8. O-O $6 O-O {After the inclusion of 00-00, Black's position is not so bad.} 9. e5 Nd5 10. Qb3 {Is our reaction when castles are not included, but here Black can continue with} Nf4 $1 $15 {[%csl Gf7][%cal Gf8f7] The knight will go to g6 or e6. Black's position is already slightly better, and all this is possible because the f7 pawn is defended.}) 8... Nd5 (8... Ng4 9. h3 Nh6 10. O-O O-O 11. Nb3 Nc6 12. Bb5 $5 $146 Nf5 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. Nfxd4 $14) 9. Qb3 $1 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gc4f7] Black cannot move the knight because the f7 pawn is hanging.} c6 10. O-O O-O 11. Nxd4 $14) 6. Bxf7+ $3 {This move has been played only once, but it may refute this line.} (6. O-O $6 {White's most common and natural continuation, but after} Nd6 $1 {Black's position is absolutely fine, as was shown in many Dominguez's games. For example:} 7. Bb3 (7. dxe5 $6 Nxc4 8. Qa4+ b5 $1 9. Qxb5+ c6 10. Qxc4 Ba6 $15 {Black is already better.}) 7... e4 $1 8. Ne5 Be7 9. Nc3 O-O $11 {No problems for Black. Of course, White has compensation, but not more than that.}) (6. Nxe5 {This is also good, and you can choose it if you don't want to sacrifice material as after 6.Bxf7.} Nd6 7. Qh5 $1 $146 {First of all, we provoke g6.} (7. Bb3 {White's most common continuation. Also here we have an edge, but Black's play might be easier:} Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Nc3 Nc6 $14 {We have a small initiative, but we should play very precisely not to lose it.}) 7... g6 8. Qe2 Be7 9. O-O Nc6 {Black's best defense, in my opinion.} (9... Nxc4 10. Qxc4 Be6 (10... O-O $4 {Loses in great style:} 11. Bh6 Be6 12. Qc3 Re8 13. d5 $1 Bxd5 14. Nxf7 Bf6 15. Nxd8 Bxc3 16. Nxc3 Rxd8 17. Rad1 c6 18. Rfe1 $18 {[%cal Ge1e7] Re7 next.}) 11. Qb5+ Nd7 12. Qxb7 $16 {We have a healthy extra pawn.}) (9... O-O $2 {Is now losing because of} 10. Bh6 $1 Re8 11. Nxf7 $3 Nxf7 12. Re1 $1 {[%csl Ye8][%cal Ge2e5,Re7f8,Ye2e8] After this move, White is winning, but without it, our position would have been lost! The threat is Qe5.} Qxd4 (12... Nc6 13. Bxf7+ Kxf7 14. Qc4+ Kf6 15. Nc3 g5 16. d5 $1 $18) 13. Nd2 $18 {[%cal Gd2f3,Gf3g5] Nf3-Ng5 next.}) 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Re1 $1 Nxc4 (11... O-O $2 12. Qxe7 Qxe7 13. Rxe7 Nxc4 14. Bh6 Rd8 15. Nc3 $18 {[%cal Gc3e4] Rxc7 or Ne4 next. According to the engine, White's position is already winning.}) 12. Qxc4 O-O $1 13. Nc3 Rb8 $16 {White is for sure better, but Black has two bishops and might have some practical counterplay. For this reason, I think 6.Bxf7! deserves attention, but if you find this position good enough, then you can also play 6.Nxe5, as we have seen.}) 6... Kxf7 7. Nxe5+ Ke8 $1 $146 {Of course, this is Black's best continuation, but it's already a novelty.} (7... Ke7 $2 {Very bad place for Black's king:} 8. O-O $18 {[%cal Gf1e1] Re1 next, and Black can resign.}) (7... Kg8 8. Qb3+ {mate in 2.}) 8. O-O {[%cal Gf1e1] We have a very simple plan: Re1, followed by some discovery check.} Be7 (8... Qf6 $2 {[%cal Gf6f2] Black puts pressure against f2, but after} 9. Qe2 Nd6 10. Re1 Be7 11. Nc3 c6 12. h4 $1 {[%cal Gc1g5] preparing Bg5.} Qxh4 13. Nf3 Bg4 14. Qe5 Qf6 15. Qg3 Bxf3 16. Bg5 $18 {Black can resign.}) 9. Re1 Nf6 {Black can also reach this position by the 8...Nf6 9.Re1 Be7 move order. Here, we have a long-term compensation and a +1,00 advantage, according to Stockfish.} (9... Nd6 $2 {Black's knight is misplaced on d6, at least because} 10. Bg5 $1 $18) 10. Nc3 $5 {What is our idea? We just want to play Bg5-Qb3 and hope that Black's position will collapse.} (10. Qb3 $5 Qd5 11. Qg3 $16) 10... a5 $1 {[%cal Ga8a6] Black's best continuation. The idea is to activate the rook via a6.} (10... Nc6 11. Qb3 $1 Rf8 (11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nd7 13. Rd1 $18 {Domination.}) 12. Bg5 $16 {[%cal Ya7a5,Ya8a6] Very difficult to play for Black. Probably, the best plan is a5-Ra6.}) 11. Qb3 Rf8 12. Bg5 Ra6 13. Rac1 $5 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Gc3b5] We can put pressure against the c7 pawn.} Rb6 14. Nb5 Nc6 (14... c6 $4 15. Nd6+ $18) 15. Qc4 $16 {Very difficult to play for Black, but the game still goes on. In conclusion, against 5...Nxe4, 6.Bxf7!! might refute Black's system, but you need to be ready to play a long game without a piece. If you prefer to have a smaller advantage but with equal material, you can choose 6.Nxe5 Nd6 7.Qh5!, which also has a lot of venom.} *

