{[%evp 0,53,32,29,18,-6,27,7,3,3,38,26,17,27,63,-70,-27,-27,74,45,41,41,26,21,7,13,32,13,-3,0,27,-17,2,-8,3,50,39,-30,-21,-78,-23,-47,-43,-44,-36,-31,-33,-37,0,0,0,0,0,-21,1,-17]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 e5 4. Nf3 Bb4+ {The topic of this chapter.} 5. Nc3 {The most interesting option for White.} (5. Bd2 {I played this move a lot of times, but unfortunately no advantage:} Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 (6. Nbxd2 exd4 7. Bxc4 Nc6 8. O-O Qf6 $11 {Big theory, Black is okay.}) 6... exd4 7. Nxd4 Nf6 8. Nc3 Qe7 {The critical line continues with} 9. f3 O-O 10. O-O-O c5 11. Ndb5 a6 12. Qd6 Nc6 13. Qxe7 Nxe7 14. Nd6 b5 15. e5 Ne8 $11 {With the dark squares bishops exchanged, I think this is not so interesting for White.}) (5. Nbd2 $6 {Compared to the main line 4...cxd4, White can't block the check with the knight, because of} c3 $1 $36 {[%csl Gb4,Gc3][%cal Gb4c3] Strong move.}) 5... Nf6 $5 {Very critical line nowadays, when I started to play this opening 30 years ago, this move didn't even exist, but now engines got stronger and more people are starting to play like this. You can expect this move, from either a very strong player (GM 2600+ level) or from a very well prepared opponent. This line is not frequent on lower levels.} (5... exd4 {Most common move.} 6. Nxd4 Nd7 {[%cal Gg8f6,Rd1a4] Popular line, Black wants to develop the knight to a natural square on f6, but first without allowing Qa4+ of course.} (6... Ne7 {[%cal Gb8c6] Classical line, Black is preparing Nbc6.} 7. Bf4 $5 {This is my main recommendation, it's a positional line, without risk. For the moment, it stops Nb6.} (7. a3 $5 {Interesting option.} Nbc6 $1 {[%csl Rd4] This is a strong intermezzo.} (7... Bxc3+ {leads to a playable position.} 8. bxc3 O-O 9. Bxc4 $14 {But I think White has some chances for advantage.}) (7... Ba5 $6 {This is not precise, since after} 8. Bxc4 Nbc6 9. Be3 O-O 10. O-O {White has an improved version compared to the main 7.Bxc4.} Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Nc6 12. Bc5 $1 $16 {[%csl Ra5,Gc5] This is the point.}) 8. axb4 {Critical.} (8. Be3 {was played in the game Ivanchuk-Postny, 2012.} Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Ne5 10. f4 Nd3+ 11. Bxd3 cxd3 12. Qxd3 O-O 13. Qe2 $11 {[%cal Gd8e8,Gc7c5] This is how the game continued, playable, but equal position.}) 8... Qxd4 9. Qa4 O-O 10. b5 $5 $146 {It's my try, novelty.} (10. Be3 {Logical try.} Qd6 11. b5 Ne5 12. Bxc4 Nxc4 13. Qxc4 Be6 14. Qc5 f5 $11 {This is how one email game continued, Black is fine here.}) 10... Ne5 11. Be2 Bg4 {The best.} (11... Nd3+ $6 {Logical, but mistake.} 12. Bxd3 Qxd3 13. Be3 $14 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Ga1d1] The queen is in trouble.}) (11... Be6 {Logical move as well.} 12. O-O Qd6 13. Be3 Nd3 14. f4 {[%csl Gd3,Ge4,Gf4] Standard play, White plays for control in the center, and Black for the strong knight on d3.} f6 15. Qc2 Rfd8 16. Rfd1 {White is ready for b3, and engine line is fantastic:} Bf7 $3 {Mega prophlyactic move against b3, but what's the point?} 17. b3 Nf5 $3 {[%csl Gf5,Gf7] The point of Black's previous move, fantastic resource for Black, but difficult to believe that somebody will find it over the board.} 18. exf5 Qe7 {[%cal Re7e3,Rc4b3] Double attack.} 19. Qd2 Nb2 $1 20. Qxb2 Qxe3+ 21. Kh1 cxb3 $13 {For the engine, this is enough compensation for Black.}) 12. Be3 Qd6 13. f3 Be6 14. O-O {Position is tense and playable:} Nd3 15. f4 f6 16. b3 $5 {Double-edged idea.} Nc5 17. Qa2 cxb3 18. Qb2 {White sacrificed two pawns, difficult to evaluate this position:} Nc8 19. Rfd1 Qe7 20. Bf3 Kh8 21. Qa3 b6 22. f5 Bc4 $13 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ge4e5] The line goes on with e5, but it's too complicated at this point.}) (7. Bxc4 {The main move.} Nbc6 8. Be3 O-O 9. O-O {Black can force an endgame:} Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Nc6 11. Be3 Qxd1 12. Rfxd1 {Visually, it looks pleasant for White, but the endgame is normal for Black:} Na5 13. Be2 Bxc3 14. bxc3 {This is how the game Sanikidze-Balogh, Olympiad 2016 continued.} b6 $5 $11 {White can play it, but Black is objectively fine.}) 7... O-O {Logical, the only move that makes sense.} (7... Nbc6 $6 {is met with} 8. Ndb5 $14 {[%csl Rc7] c7 is impossible to defend.}) 8. Bxc4 Nbc6 9. Nde2 $5 $146 {Novelty, interesting idea.} (9. Ndb5 $146 {Novelty, but unfortunately, not so inspiring for White.} Ng6 $1 10. Bxc7 Qg5 11. O-O a6 $36 {Black has full compensation, and it could be a bit risky for White.}) 9... Qxd1+ {Black goes for the endgame:} 10. Rxd1 Na5 11. Bd3 Be6 12. a3 Bxc3+ 13. Nxc3 c6 {Visually, Black is doing okay, but it's a new position, White has the pair of bishops, I am ready to play it with White, for example:} 14. h4 $5 {[%csl Ge1][%cal Gh4h5,Gf2f3,Ge1f2] Good move just to get some space, the king stays well in the center, it can go to f2 as well.} b6 15. h5 {Sample line:} Rfd8 {[%cal Ge6b3,Ga5c4] Black has a concrete threat.} 16. Be2 Nc4 17. Bc1 Rxd1+ 18. Nxd1 $14 {[%csl Gc1,Ge2][%cal Gh5h6] Very tiny edge for White, I know that at the moment it looks like nothing, but long term, the pair of bishops can pose serious questions, especially the dark squares bishop. White can play this endgame, I would be happy to be White here.}) (6... Qe7 $2 {This is just a bad move.} 7. Bxc4 Qxe4+ 8. Kf1 $16 {[%csl Re4] Close to winning advantage for White, it is a very bad idea to capture this pawn.}) (6... Nf6 $2 {is not recommended.} 7. Qa4+ $16 {White is better.}) 7. Bxc4 Ngf6 8. f3 (8. Bxf7+ $5 {was played in the game Dubov-Cheparinov, Samarkand Rapid 2023 at maximum you can check your opponent's memory:} Kxf7 9. Qb3+ Ke8 10. Qxb4 c5 11. Qa3 cxd4 12. Nb5 {For a rapid game, it is more or less interesting, but Black was prepared:} Nxe4 13. O-O Ndf6 14. Bf4 Kf7 $11 {Equal position, for example:} 15. Nc7 $1 $146 {The best.} Nd5 16. Qb3 Nc5 17. Qf3 Nxf4 18. Qxf4+ Qf6 19. Qxf6+ gxf6 20. Nxa8 Rg8 $1 $11 {[%cal Gc8h3,Gb7b6,Gc8b7] Important intermezzo, Black is fine.}) 8... O-O 9. Be2 {Very good prophylactic move.} (9. O-O Qe7 $5 {[%cal Re7c5] is one extra option.}) 9... Ne5 (9... Qe7 $6 {runs under tempo.} 10. Nf5 $1 $14 {One big difference on why we start with 9.Be2.}) 10. O-O {Most logical move.} (10. Be3 Qe7 11. O-O c5 $11 {Black has their own play.}) 10... Qe7 $1 {The best move, and was played also in some high level games.} (10... Bc5 11. Be3 Nc6 12. Nc2 $14 {White is slightly better here.}) 11. Bg5 $5 {That's why we start with castle first and not Be3.} Bxc3 {The best try, it was played in the game Mamedyarov-So, Norway Chess 2023.} (11... c6 12. Qc2 $14 {Slight advantage.}) 12. bxc3 c5 {Now White has two options:} 13. Nc2 {was Mamedyarov's choice, the knight stays better on c2.} (13. Nb3 $5 {deserves attention, the only problem is that the knight will be a bit misplaced here.} Rd8 14. Qb1 {Strange a bit, but interesting.} b6 {Most natural, and good from a positional point of view.} (14... h6 15. Bxf6 Qxf6 16. f4 $14 {[%cal Ge4e5] This looks pleasant for White.}) 15. f4 $1 {Time for White to act, if we wait, Black would be absolutely fine.} Ng6 16. Rf2 $5 {[%cal Gf2e2] Very interesting prophylactic move, defending the bishop on e2. e5 is a serious threat now.} (16. e5 {looks logical as well.} h6 $1 {[%cal Re5f6,Ge7e2] Only move.} 17. Bxf6 gxf6 $13 {[%csl Rb3] Unclear position, the knight on b3 is White's biggest issue.}) 16... h6 {Necessary.} 17. Bxf6 Qxf6 18. Qc1 {White can play a positional game:} Bb7 19. Qe3 Qc6 20. e5 Ne7 21. Re1 {Step by step, White can try to press.} f5 $1 $132 {The best move for Black, but already not an easy one to find.}) 13... Rd8 14. Qe1 {Natural play.} h6 $1 {Wesley was very well prepared.} 15. Bxf6 {The best.} (15. Bh4 Ng6 $11 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Rh4g3,Gf6h5,Rh4f2,Gg6f4] Anyway it is not easy to hold on to the bishop's pair.}) 15... Qxf6 16. Ne3 {White's position is playable, visually pleasant as well, for example:} Nd3 {was Wesley's choice.} 17. Bxd3 Rxd3 18. Nd5 Qd8 19. Rd1 c4 20. Qe2 Rxd1 21. Rxd1 b5 {Logical so far, we can improve White's play now:} 22. Qb2 $5 $146 {Engine improvement, and White can be slightly better.} (22. a4 {was Shakh's move, but position is equal in many ways.} a6 $11 {The game ultimately ended in a draw.} (22... bxa4 $11)) 22... Qa5 {The best.} 23. Qb4 $1 {We go to endgame.} Qxb4 24. Nxb4 a5 25. Nc2 $14 {White has practical chances, a scenario that you can expect is that White will achieve 4v3 on the kingside, with knight against bishop. Endgame is holdable for Black, but unpleasant.}) 6. Nxe5 $5 {My recommendation, I think it's more interesting than 6.Bxc4, Black has a lot of safety there.} (6. Bxc4 {is one option, but I think Black's position is fine:} exd4 7. Nxd4 O-O 8. O-O {Only try, to sacrifice the pawn.} (8. f3 Qe7 $11 {Black is doing fine, all pieces are developed.}) 8... Bxc3 9. bxc3 Nxe4 {14 games here, and most of them are played on the highest level:} 10. Bd3 {was how the game Giri-MVL, 2023 continued.} Nf6 11. Bg5 h6 12. Bh4 {Black has many good moves in the position.} Nc6 {MVL's choice is good enough, he just tried to play for a draw.} 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Qc2 Re8 15. Rad1 Qe7 {There isn't too much energy in the position.} 16. Qa4 Qc5 17. Bxf6 gxf6 $11 {Strucutre is ruined for Black, but White doesn't have any pieces left, equal position.}) 6... b5 $1 {Black's idea.} 7. Be2 $5 {This is my recommendation. Very rare move, played only in 2 games: Bareev-Ivanchuk, Linares 1992 and Nepomniatchi-Dominguez, 2022.} (7. f3 {The main move, and also the choice of world's elite players like Carlsen, Nakamura, Firouzja etc.} O-O 8. a3 $5 {Interesting try.} (8. a4 {was tried in Nakamura-Mamedyarov, Norway Chess 2023.} c5 $1 {Shakh analyzed this position until the end, we can check the game:} 9. Be3 cxd4 10. Qxd4 Qe7 11. axb5 {It was just a game between two engines!} Rd8 12. Qxc4 Be6 13. Qe2 Qc7 14. Nc4 Nbd7 15. Ra6 $5 {First line by both always.} Nc5 16. Rc6 Qe7 17. Qf2 Ncxe4 $1 18. fxe4 Nxe4 19. Qf4 Nxc3 20. bxc3 Bxc3+ 21. Kf2 Rd5 $1 {Very strong move.} 22. Qe4 Qf6+ 23. Kg1 Rad8 24. Bxa7 Rf5 25. Bd3 Rfd5 26. Bf1 Rf5 27. Bd3 Rfd5 $11 {Fantastic game, but unfortunately it was all analyzed at home by both players, memorized and displayed for us to see how deep Top Players prepare for the games.}) 8... Ba5 9. a4 $1 {The idea compared to 8.a4 is that Black doesn't have c5 anymore.} a6 $1 {Best move, and it was played in the same tournament: Firouzja-Mamedyarov, Norway Chess 2023.} (9... c5 $2 10. dxc5 $16 {[%cal Rd8e7,Gd1d6] Black sacrificed the pawn for nothing.}) 10. Be2 Nfd7 {was Mamedyarov's move.} (10... c5 $5 $146 {This is an interesting try now.} 11. dxc5 Qc7 12. Qd6 Qb7 13. Be3 Bc7 14. Qe7 bxa4 {Very complicated line.} 15. Bxc4 Bxe5 16. Qxe5 Nc6 $13 {Tough to evaluate.}) 11. Nxd7 $5 $146 {This is my try.} (11. O-O {Logical, but doesn't lead to something concrete.} Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nc6 $11 {Equal game.}) (11. Be3 {Firouzja played a natural move, but Black could improve over the game:} Nxe5 $1 $146 {Go to endgame.} (11... c6 $6 {was not precise.} 12. O-O $14 {White is slightly better.}) 12. dxe5 Qxd1+ 13. Kxd1 Nc6 14. axb5 axb5 15. Nxb5 $11 {Playable for White, but Black is fine.}) 11... Nxd7 12. O-O {Playable for White, especially since Black has only one good move:} c6 $1 {To defend b5, not the hardest move, but still.} 13. Be3 Nb6 14. Qc1 $5 {Mysterious move.} Bd7 (14... Bxc3 $6 {is not good.} 15. bxc3 Nxa4 16. Bxc4 $1 $16 {[%cal Rb5c4,Ga1a4] White is better.}) 15. Rd1 Qf6 {White can play some waiting moves now:} 16. Bf1 h6 17. Bf2 $132 {Just tense, playable position.}) 7... Nxe4 {Most logical move, played by Dominguez.} (7... O-O $146 {is also a possible move order.} 8. O-O (8. Bg5 $5 {deserves attention.}) 8... Bxc3 9. bxc3 Nxe4 10. Ba3 {[%cal Re4c3,Gc3e2] Transposes to main line.}) 8. O-O {The position is very concrete, 2 choices for Black: to take on c3 by knight or by bishop.} Bxc3 $1 {The best move, played by Dominguez.} (8... Nxc3 $5 $146 {also an option.} 9. bxc3 Bxc3 10. Rb1 {Natural move.} (10. Bh5 {This is a very forced line:} O-O $1 11. Qf3 f6 $1 12. Ng6 $1 {Nice idea.} hxg6 13. Bxg6 Be6 $1 {Only good move.} 14. Qh5 Re8 $1 15. Ba3 b4 $1 16. Rac1 {With idea Rxc3.} Bxd4 17. Bxe8 {Position is equal, but not so easy to understand it over the board.} Nd7 18. Bxd7 Qxd7 19. Bxb4 $13 {Complicated position.}) 10... O-O 11. Ba3 {Interesting position, everything is hanging for Black, what to do?} c6 $1 {The best move, the h1-a8 diagonal is more important than material, but very tough move.} (11... b4 $6 {looks logical, but not the best.} 12. Rxb4 $1 {Correct recapture.} (12. Bxb4 $6 {is equal after} Bxb4 13. Rxb4 Nd7 $11) 12... Bxb4 13. Bxb4 {This however could be better for White.} Nd7 {The best, to finish development.} (13... Re8 $6 {too dangerous.} 14. Bxc4 Be6 15. d5 $1 {Very strong move, and the lines only start here.} Bf5 16. Nxf7 $3 $40 {[%cal Gd5d6,Gd1f3] White has a lot of attacking potential.}) 14. Nc6 $1 {[%csl Gc6,Rd7] To keep more pieces on the board!} Qf6 15. Bf3 $1 $36 {[%csl Ra8,Gc6,Gf3,Rf8] Black is dominated by White's pieces, it's tough to suggest a move even.}) 12. Bxf8 Qxf8 13. a4 a6 14. Bg4 $132 {[%csl Ra8,Rb8] Interesting complicated position, but one wrong move from Black, and it could be all over very soon. After all the pieces are not developed.}) 9. bxc3 Nxc3 10. Qc2 Nxe2+ 11. Qxe2 O-O 12. Ba3 {[%csl Ra8,Rf7][%cal Rf8e8,Ge2f3] White will win an exchange, because Re8 is impossible, because of Qf3, but it's not all.} Nd7 $1 {Good move by Dominguez.} (12... Bb7 $5 $146 {Possible move as well.} 13. Bxf8 Qd5 $1 14. Qg4 Kxf8 15. Rfe1 h5 $1 {Very tough for a human to play so well I believe.} 16. Qg5 Kg8 $1 17. Nxf7 Qxf7 18. Re7 Qf6 19. Qxb5 Nc6 $1 {Only move.} 20. Qd5+ Kf8 21. Rd7 Re8 22. Qxc4 Bc8 23. Qc5+ Kg8 24. Qd5+ Kf8 25. Rxc7 Nxd4 26. Rd1 Ne6 27. Qd6+ Kg8 $11 {[%cal Gd6d5,Gg8f8] Position is equal for the engine, but still playable.}) 13. Bxf8 Qxf8 14. Qe4 $5 $146 {Interesting move, and clear improvement over the game.} (14. a4 $2 {Nepo played this game, but it was mistake.} Nxe5 $1 $15 {Black was better and later won the game.}) 14... Rb8 15. Nc6 Bb7 16. Rfe1 {Very strange position. Who is better and why?} Kh8 {The best move, prophylaxis against check on e7.} (16... Qd6 $2 {Logical, but Black loses immediately.} 17. Qe8+ $1 $18 {Back rank issues.}) 17. Qd5 Nb6 18. Qf3 {Position is very complicated.} (18. Qxb5 {is met with} a6 $11) 18... b4 {The best probably.} (18... h6 19. d5 {This could be slightly better for White.} Bxc6 20. dxc6 b4 21. Qf4 Rc8 22. Qf5 $14 {[%cal Rc4c3,Ga1d1] Of course, it's not all, but engine evaluates this as better chances for White.}) 19. Re5 Re8 20. Rae1 Rxe5 21. Rxe5 Nd7 $1 {Only good move.} 22. Re1 Nf6 23. d5 c3 24. Qf4 $5 {Tricky move.} Bxc6 $1 {The best.} (24... Nxd5 $2 {is bad, because of} 25. Qc4 $1 $16 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gc4c6] Back rank alongside with many threast.}) 25. dxc6 Qb8 $1 {[%csl Gb4,Gc7][%cal Gb8c7,Gb8b4] Only move, to defend both pawns.} 26. g4 $5 {We can start our attack.} h6 27. h4 $36 {[%cal Gh8g8] Kg8 is best move, okay, you can go also deeper, but I think it is enough, g5 is an idea, and not only. One mistake from Black and it's all over.} *

