{[%evp 0,47,20,24,17,6,32,-6,-6,-6,-12,-10,7,1,1,1,30,43,37,37,38,38,38,38,30,30,33,23,23,23,23,6,65,-5,42,30,36,60,60,65,67,15,-7,0,0,-7,-20,-26,10,24]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 e5 4. Nf3 exd4 5. Bxc4 Bb4+ {This is GM Rublevsky's favorite line. I have faced him multiple times in this variation, gaining valuable insights from our games.} 6. Nbd2 {[%csl Gd2] More interesting than 6.Bd2, in my opinion.} Nc6 (6... Nf6 $4 {[%csl Rb4] Famous blunder:} 7. Bxf7+ Kxf7 8. Qb3+ $18 {[%csl Rb4,Rf7][%cal Gb3b4,Gb3f7]}) 7. O-O Nf6 (7... Be6 $2 {bad move.} 8. Bxe6 fxe6 9. Qb3 (9. Nb3 $16 {also good.}) 9... Qd7 10. Nc4 $16 {[%cal Ga2a3] a3 next, with big advantage.}) 8. e5 Nd5 9. Nb3 Nb6 {Black's main continuation by far.} (9... O-O $2 {bad move order:} 10. Nbxd4 Nb6 11. Nxc6 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 bxc6 13. Bb3 $16 {[%csl Ra7,Rc6,Rc7][%cal Gb3c2,Gc2e4] Maybe Bc2-Be4 next, and White has a better endgame due to Black's bad queenside pawn structure.}) (9... Be7 {Rare sideline, and White has a lot of ideas here.} 10. Qe2 $5 {More ambitious way.} (10. Nbxd4 {Simple way.} Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Nb6 12. Bb3 Qxd4 (12... O-O $2 13. Qe4 $16 {[%csl Ge4]}) 13. Nxd4 O-O 14. e6 fxe6 15. Nxe6 Bxe6 16. Bxe6+ $14 {Not too much, but White is slightly better thanks to the two bishops.}) 10... O-O 11. Rd1 Re8 (11... Bg4 12. Nbxd4 Nxd4 13. Rxd4 Be6 14. Qe4 c6 15. h4 $5 $146 {[%cal Gc1g5,Gf3g5] Bg5 or Ng5 next, with some initiative.}) 12. Nbxd4 (12. Be3 $5 $146 {could be interesting} Nxe3 13. fxe3 Bg4 14. exd4 $36 {New playable position.}) 12... Nxd4 13. Nxd4 c6 14. Qf3 $36 {[%cal Gf3g3] Playable position, not so easy to continue for Black.}) 10. Bg5 ({I don't like} 10. Bb5 {because after} Qd5 $1 11. Nbxd4 O-O 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Qc2 c5 $132 {I feel that this is not a position for a long game, and Black can concretely equalize in more than one way.}) 10... Be7 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 (11... Nxe7 $2 {wrong recapture.} 12. Bd3 O-O (12... Bf5 13. Nbxd4 Bxd3 14. Qxd3 $16) 13. Qc2 Ng6 14. Nbxd4 $16 {[%cal Gd3e4,Gf1e1,Ga1d1] Be4-Rfe1-Rad1 next, and White has a good positional advantage.}) 12. Bb5 Bd7 {And now, White has two interesting directions.} (12... O-O $6 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. Rc1 $14 {Should be at least slightly better for White.}) 13. Bxc6 {White's main continuation, and I have also played it many times.} (13. Re1 $5 {Also interesting if you want to play something rare.} O-O-O {I think this is more critical than short castle.} (13... O-O {natural continuation.} 14. Rc1 Rad8 15. Qd2 $5 $146 {Was played in two online games, but OTB it's a novelty.} ({In 2010, I have played} 15. Nc5 {but Black was fine after} a6 $1 16. Bd3 Bc8 17. Be4 d3 18. Qd2 Nd4 19. Nxd4 Rxd4 20. Bxd3 Rfd8 21. Qc2 h6 22. a3 c6 $11 {Dreev-Stevic, 2010.}) 15... d3 $1 {strongest move.} (15... Rfe8 $2 {looks useful, but it's bad.} 16. Nc5 Bc8 (16... a6 17. Nxa6 $1 bxa6 18. Bxc6 $16) 17. Nxb7 $1 $16) (15... Qb4 16. Qd3 $36 {[%cal Gf3g5] Ng5 idea.}) 16. Nc5 Bf5 $1 {Black's best continuation.} (16... a6 $6 17. e6 $1 fxe6 18. Bxc6 Bxc6 19. Nxe6 Bxf3 20. gxf3 $16 {White got a big advantage in the email game Pavlicek-Dedina, 2014.}) 17. Qf4 d2 {engine move.} 18. Nxd2 Nd4 19. Nf3 Ne6 20. Qxf5 Nxc5 21. h4 $14 {[%cal Gb5f1] Maybe Bf1 next, and it's for sure playable and slightly better.}) 14. Rc1 a6 $1 {Strong, but difficult move.} (14... d3 15. Qd2 a6 (15... g6 $2 16. Nc5 $16 {Anand-Dominguez, 2009.}) 16. Bxd3 Kb8 (16... Nb4 $2 {active but bad.} 17. Be4 Bc6 18. Nfd4 $18 {Winning for White, according to the engine.}) 17. Qe3 Nd5 18. Qe4 $40 {[%cal Gb3c5] Nc5 next, with very good chances.}) 15. Bxc6 Bxc6 16. Nfxd4 {Safe way.} (16. Rxc6 $5 $146 {ambitious try.} bxc6 17. Qd3 {Looks very dangerous from a human perspective, but the engine thinks that Black is fine with only moves:} Rd5 $1 18. Qxa6+ Kd7 $1 19. Nbxd4 Qc5 20. Qd3 Kc8 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7] with the idea Kb7.} 21. h3 $5 Kb7 (21... Rhd8 $2 22. e6 $1 $16) 22. a3 Qc4 (22... Rhd8 23. e6 $1 $36) 23. Qe3 $13 {Objectively there is no advantage, but it's an interesting position to play.}) 16... Bd5 17. Nc5 Kb8 18. Qd2 $36 {[%cal Ga2a4,Ga4a5,Gd2c3,Gd2b4] We have a lot of ideas like Qc3, Qb4, a4-a5. Absolutely playable position with good chances for us.}) 13... Bxc6 14. Nfxd4 Bd5 {If not Bd5, we can take on c6 and play with a better pawn structure.} 15. Qg4 h5 $1 {is Black's best reaction, but it was played only three times!} (15... O-O {Black's most common continuation, but here we have three possible directions, and each of them is interesting.} 16. f4 {[%cal Gd4f5] most concrete way: our idea is Nf5.} (16. Rfe1 {positional way.} Be6 (16... Rfe8 $6 17. Rac1 $1 $14 {[%csl Gc1] difference compared to the 16.Rae1 variation.}) 17. Nxe6 fxe6 18. Nd4 Rae8 19. Rad1 Qf7 20. f3 $14 {very small plus for White.}) (16. Rae1 $5 $146 {new way.} Rfe8 $1 {probably the best, because after 16.Rae1 White doesn't have Rc1 options.} (16... g6 $6 {not great now.} 17. Nf5 Qd7 18. Nh6+ Kg7 19. Qg5 Be6 20. Re4 Qd8 21. Qc1 $1 $16 {[%csl Bc1,Rg7] Big chances for an attack.}) (16... Be6 17. Nxe6 fxe6 18. Nd4 Rae8 19. h4 $14 {[%cal Gg2g3,Gh4h5] g3-h5 next, with some pressure.}) 17. f4 {Black is fine only if he plays like an engine:} Qf8 18. f5 (18. Nf5 $5 {also deserves attention.}) 18... Nd7 19. Qg3 c5 $1 {important move, otherwise we might think about f6-Nf5 ideas.} 20. Nb5 Bc4 21. Nc7 Bxf1 22. Nxe8 Rxe8 23. Kxf1 c4 24. Nd4 $132 {Playable but I cannot say that we are better here.}) 16... g6 (16... Bxb3 {Engine line, but difficult for a human:} 17. Nf5 Qc5+ 18. Kh1 g6 19. axb3 Nd5 $1 {[%csl Bd5] only move.} 20. Nh6+ Kh8 21. f5 Ne3 22. Qh4 Qc6 $1 {[%csl Cc6] only move.} 23. Rf3 Nxf5 24. Nxf5 gxf5 25. Rxf5 $14 {the engine will hold, but OTB there are chances.}) 17. Nf5 ({But not} 17. Rae1 $6 {because of} f5 $1 $11) 17... Qd7 18. Nh6+ Kh8 $1 (18... Kg7 $2 {most common continuation, but a mistake!} 19. f5 $1 Kxh6 20. Rf4 g5 21. h4 $1 Rg8 22. hxg5+ Kg7 23. Qh3 $18 {Winning position.}) 19. f5 gxf5 20. Qh4 Qd8 21. Qg3 $36 {Again, the engine will hold, but OTB it's very risky for Black.}) (15... g6 {second most common continuation.} 16. Rfe1 c6 $1 {Only good move, but it's difficult for a human to understand why it's the best. Still, after} (16... Rd8 $2 17. e6 $1 {Dreev-Grischuk, 2002.} f6 18. Nf5 gxf5 19. Qh5+ Kf8 20. Nd4 $18) (16... O-O $2 {most common move, but a mistake.} 17. Nf5 $1 Qd7 18. Nh6+ Kg7 19. Qg5 Be6 20. Nc5 $1 Qd8 21. h4 $16) 17. h4 h5 18. Qh3 $36 {We are slightly better with a nice initiative.}) 16. Qh3 $1 {The only interesting move—I found it back in 2003!} (16. Qxg7 $6 O-O-O $1 $36 {Black has full compensation and maybe some initiative.}) 16... a5 $1 $146 {[%cal Ga5a4] A fantastic new idea revealed by the engine.} (16... Bxb3 $2 {Dreev-Christensen, 2003.} 17. Nxb3 $16 {[%csl Rh5] White is better just because Black's pawn on h5 is misplaced, and Black needs to spend time to castle.}) 17. Rac1 a4 18. Nf5 {White's most concrete try.} (18. Nd2 $5 {another possible try.} Qd7 19. e6 fxe6 20. N2f3 $132 {Playable because Black still must find good moves to keep equality.}) 18... Qg5 (18... Qb4 $2 19. Nbd4 $16) 19. Nbd4 {and now Black must find the only move} O-O-O $3 $13 {I cannot believe that this is so simple to play :) But for the engine, the position is objectively equal.} (19... g6 $2 {Is Black's second best, but here White is better.} 20. Ne3 Qf4 21. Nb5 $16) 20. f4 {If our opponents find it, we can try to play the following endgame:} Qg4 21. Qxg4 hxg4 22. Ne7+ Kb8 23. Nxd5 Nxd5 24. f5 $11 {Still playable, but equal.} *

