{[%evp 0,61,28,25,27,-17,32,19,-10,-10,-7,-19,1,1,-13,-29,28,-20,0,-72,-21,33,21,87,-9,-12,48,73,68,80,80,102,90,94,92,76,56,99,113,113,83,57,33,32,167,106,98,74,63,43,48,51,58,51,47,58,40,56,55,55,64,47,68,54]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 e5 4. Nf3 exd4 5. Bxc4 Nc6 6. O-O Bc5 {The favorite line of GM Mamedyarov. It's a logical move because Black wants to finish the development, so White needs to act quickly.} (6... Nf6 $6 {The French GM Bauer used to play this line, but nowadays it is considered refuted:} 7. Qb3 $1 {Only move to get the advantage.} Qd7 {[%csl Ga5,Yf7][%cal Gc6a5,Yd7f7,Ya5b3,Ya5c4] Black defends the pawn on f7 and threats Na5.} (7... Na5 $2 8. Bxf7+ Ke7 9. Qa3+ $16) 8. Bd2 $1 {[%cal Rc6a5] Preventing Na5.} (8. Ng5 {Was tried by Alexey Dreev, but Black can hold after} Ne5 9. Bb5 c6 10. f4 h6 $3 $146 (10... cxb5 {was seen in Dreev-Bauer, 2011.}) 11. fxe5 hxg5 12. exf6 Qc7 $1 13. h3 gxf6 $13 {Very unclear position.}) 8... Ng4 {[%cal Gg4e5] Only logical move for Black. Of course, he can also try something like 8...Nd8, but after 9.Re1 (with the idea e5), White has a big advantage.} (8... Nd8 9. Re1 $1 $16 {[%cal Ge4e5] e5 next.} (9. e5 $2 {Is premature because of} Ne4 $13)) 9. e5 $1 {Again, only after this move we have the advantage.} Qf5 10. Re1 Be7 11. Bd3 $1 (11. h3 $2 Ngxe5 $1 {it's already White who needs to think about equality.}) 11... Qh5 (11... Qe6 12. Na3 {Very simple continuation because Black will have problems also in the endgame:} (12. Qc2 $5 $16 {Is also good if you prefer to keep the queens on the board.}) 12... Qxb3 13. axb3 $16 {[%cal Ga3b5] Nb5 is our idea. According to the engine, White has a +1,50 advantage...}) 12. h3 Nh6 (12... Ngxe5 $4 {is not possible.} 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. Qb5+ $18) 13. Na3 O-O 14. Rac1 $16 {[%cal Gd3e4] Be4 next, and White dominates.}) 7. Qb3 {This is my recommendation; it's no worse than 7.Ng5 and the arising positions are easier to understand.} (7. Ng5 {Is also possible, but the arising positions are playable for Black, in my opinion:} Nh6 8. Nxf7 Nxf7 9. Bxf7+ Kxf7 10. Qh5+ g6 11. Qxc5 Re8 {It's a non-standard position. I believe White should have a way to maintain an edge, but the position is not concrete, and things can easily go out of control.}) 7... Qf6 $1 {Only move.} (7... Qe7 8. Bg5 $1 f6 9. Bf4 $16) (7... Qd7 8. Re1 $1 {Prophylactic move against Nf6.} (8. e5 $6 {premature} Na5 9. Bxf7+ Qxf7 10. Qb5+ Nc6 11. Qxc5 Nge7 $13 {[%csl Gf5] Black's position is fine, because the knight will have the important f5 square.}) 8... Na5 (8... Nf6 $4 9. e5 $18) 9. Bxf7+ Qxf7 10. Qb5+ Nc6 11. Qxc5 Nge7 12. Nxd4 b6 13. Qc3 Nxd4 14. Qxd4 O-O 15. Be3 $16 {Compared to 8.e5, here Black's knight on e7 is bad because it doesn't have the important f5 square available. A small detail like this can completely change the evaluation of the position.}) 8. e5 Qg6 $1 {Black's best defense.} (8... Qf5 9. h3 $1 {[%cal Gg2g4] Threatening g4.} Nh6 10. Bd3 $1 (10. Bxh6 $6 gxh6 $13) 10... Qe6 11. Qd1 $16 {Black's pieces are very misplaced, for example:} Nf5 12. a3 $1 {against Nb4 ideas.} O-O 13. Bf4 $16 {[%cal Gf1e1,Gb1d2] Re1-Nbd2 next.}) 9. Ng5 Nh6 10. e6 $1 fxe6 $1 {A move that seems strange for a human player, but not for Mr. Daroczi, who successfully used it in a Titled-Tuesday game.} (10... O-O $2 11. Bd3 Nf5 12. exf7+ Kh8 13. g4 $16) 11. Nxe6 Bxe6 12. Bxe6 Nf7 13. Qxb7 Qxe6 $1 14. Qxa8+ Nfd8 {Very strange position. We have an extra exchange, but Black's pieces are very active.} 15. Nd2 $1 {Only good move, otherwise Black is immediately fine.} O-O {The best and the most natural move.} (15... Kd7 $5 16. Nb3 Bb6 17. Bd2 $1 $16 {[%cal Ga1c1] Rac1 next. According to the engine, the evaluation is +0,70, but this should definitely be tried in a game.}) 16. Nb3 Bb6 17. Bd2 $1 {Again, only move. Otherwise, we are worse. We can continue to check the engine's first line to better understand what can happen.} Nf7 18. Qb7 Nfe5 19. Rac1 {[%cal Gb3c5]} Qd5 $1 20. f4 Nc4 21. Qa6 Ne3 22. Bxe3 Nb4 $1 (22... dxe3 $2 23. Qe2 $16 {White is better.}) 23. Qe2 Re8 $1 {Very strange position. For some reasons, White's best is} 24. Nc5 $1 Nxa2 $3 {Amazing variation.} (24... Rxe3 $6 25. Qc4 $16) (24... Bxc5 $2 25. Qb5 $18) 25. Rc2 c6 $3 {Black's best continuation; probably against Qb5.} (25... Rxe3 $6 26. Qc4 $16) (25... Nb4 $4 26. Qb5 $18) 26. Rd1 $1 Bxc5 27. Qf3 Nb4 $1 {Again only move.} 28. Rxc5 Qxc5 29. Bxd4 Qd5 30. Qg4 g6 31. Bxa7 $14 {We can conclude at this point. According to the engine, Black’s position is defensible, but it remains challenging in a practical game. In summary, 6...Bc5 is a highly risky choice for Black, though it may not be fully refuted due to the resourcefulness of 10...fxe6 followed by the exchange sacrifice. We’ve explored all the complications recommended by the engine, and while they are unlikely to occur in a practical game, they provide valuable insights for a deeper understanding of the variation.} *

