{[%evp 0,57,32,32,18,3,27,7,20,20,20,20,20,14,21,6,15,21,25,25,19,11,78,57,57,11,14,16,62,53,40,50,38,36,32,30,45,32,42,40,48,47,54,39,25,8,8,-1,-1,-3,-7,-7,-21,-27,-6,2,-51,-68,-35,-37]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 Nf6 {The topic of this chapter.} 4. e5 Nd5 5. Bxc4 Nb6 {The main line by far.} 6. Bb3 {My recommendation.} (6. Bd3 {I played it myself a lot of times, but I am not sure about advantage:} Nc6 7. Ne2 Bg4 $11 {Theory only starts here, Black should be okay.}) 6... Nc6 {The main move, it was played in 1300 games out 1500.} (6... Bf5 {Normal move, but a bit strange, because Black gives up on the Bg4 ideas.} 7. Nf3 e6 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. O-O Be7 10. a3 {White has a pleasant game:} O-O 11. Be3 {We transposed to the game Carlsen-Le Quang, 2019.} Na5 12. Bc2 Bxc2 (12... Qd7 $2 {was played in the game, but not a good move.} 13. Bxf5 exf5 14. d5 $1 $16 {Carlsen got a big advantage and later won the game.}) 13. Qxc2 $14 {Typical position, White is better here, thanks to the extra space.}) (6... c5 $6 {Rare move, White has a good position in many ways:} 7. Nf3 c4 {The best, but you can also take the pawn.} (7... cxd4 8. Nc3 $5 $146 {[%cal Rd4c3,Gb3f7] The knight is invulnerable.} Nc6 9. Nb5 $14 {[%cal Rc8g4,Gb3f7] White is slightly better.}) 8. Bxc4 Nxc4 9. Qa4+ $14 {Some compensation exists, but not full.}) 7. Be3 $5 {Third move by popularity, but I prefer to play this position with a knight on f3, without allowing Bg4 ideas.} (7. Ne2 {It's possible, but I prefer to develop the g1 knight to f3.} Bf5 8. O-O e6 9. Nbc3 Qd7 {Main position.} 10. Be3 O-O-O {The best.} (10... Na5 $6 {not great.} 11. Bc2 $14 {Similar to the Carlsen-Le Quang game.}) 11. Qc1 $5 {[%cal Gf1d1] Deep move with idea Rd1, some time ago it was my favorite line, but now I am not sure about it:} Kb8 12. Rd1 Qe8 $5 {[%cal Gf7f6] This interesting move is what poses problems, Grischuk played it. Black is ready for f6 now.} (12... Nb4 {I like White's position after} 13. a3 N4d5 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Bxd5 $1 {Anti-positional, but very strong move, the knight is more important than the bishop.} Qxd5 16. b4 $14 {Better for White.}) (12... Be7 {Normal development.} 13. h3 $132 {Useful move, playable position.}) (12... f6 $2 {is premature here, because of} 13. d5 $1 $16 {[%csl Gd1,Rd7] The queen is under attack.}) 13. Ng3 {Logical.} (13. a4 $6 {is premature.} Bb4 $1 $132 {[%csl Ra4,Gb4] Black is okay.}) (13. a3 {Useful move.} f6 $132 {Black starts their counterplay.}) 13... Bg6 14. Nge4 {looks like a playable position for White, and you can play it if you like, but I am not a big fan of the following variation:} Bxe4 $1 {Good reaction.} (14... f6 $6 {too early.} 15. exf6 Bxe4 16. fxg7 $1 $16 {[%csl Rf8,Gg7] Important intermediate move.}) 15. Nxe4 f6 $1 {This is Black's idea, and it is very interesting:} 16. a3 $5 {Deep move, just to stop Nb4 ideas. Some years ago, I had the opinion that White is better here, but now engine suggests a fantastic idea for Black:} (16. exf6 gxf6 17. Nxf6 Qg6 {[%csl Rf6] The knight has no squares, this is Black's point.} 18. d5 $1 {Only move.} Ne5 $1 {Position is equal, for example} 19. Bg5 h6 20. dxe6 Rxd1+ 21. Qxd1 Bg7 {Risky for both sides, and no advantage.} 22. f4 Nd3 23. Qd2 hxg5 24. fxg5 $11 {[%cal Rg7f6,Rg7f8] For engine it's equal, but I am a bit afraid to play this concrete position with White.}) (16. Nc3 {White can also play just for compensation.} fxe5 17. dxe5 Nxe5 18. Qc2 Bd6 19. Ne4 Nd5 $11 {White has full compensation, but also Black's position is normal.}) 16... h6 $3 $146 {Useful prophylactic move. It will support g5 ideas against f4.} (16... Qg6 {is inaccurate.} 17. Bc2 $1 $14 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Rc6b4] No Nb4, Black is in trouble.}) 17. f4 {Positional move.} (17. exf6 gxf6 $13 {As usual, it's unclear.}) 17... f5 $1 {[%csl Gh6][%cal Re4g5] No Ng5 as well.} 18. Nc3 Qf7 {[%csl Gh6][%cal Gg7g5] To stop d5, and next move could be g5 for Black.} 19. Qc2 g5 {Still, position remains playable for both sides.} 20. Bf2 $5 gxf4 21. Ne2 Ne7 $1 {[%cal Re2f4,Ge7d5] Nxf4 is met with Nd5.} 22. Bh4 $5 {We can play for the weak e6 pawn.} Rd7 23. Bxe7 Rxe7 24. Nxf4 c6 $132 {[%cal Gh6h5] Position is unclear, Black has counterplay chances with h5-Bh6. Position is tense, you can play it with White as well, but for the engine evaluation it's equal.}) (7. Nf3 {My idea is to play with the knight on f3, but here it is too early:} Bg4 $1 {And if you want, you can make a beautiful draw:} 8. Ng5 $5 {500 games finished this way.} Bxd1 9. Bxf7+ Kd7 10. Be6+ Ke8 11. Bf7+ $11 {Draw by repetition.}) 7... Bf5 {The best, no other development is available.} 8. Nc3 e6 9. a3 $1 {[%csl Ga3][%cal Rc6b4,Rf8b4] Important prophylactic move, typical for this structure, it's very good at stopping any Nb4/Bb4 ideas.} (9. Nf3 $6 {It's a bit too early for this move.} Na5 {Also good enough.} (9... Nb4 $132 {is one good option.}) 10. Bc2 Bxc2 11. Qxc2 Bb4 $1 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Rb4c3] Strong idea, and Black's position is not worse.} 12. O-O Bxc3 $1 $11 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gb6d5] And Black can play for a blockade on the light squares. Typical positional ideas for this line.}) 9... Qd7 {[%csl Gd7][%cal Gc6a5] The best move, now Black is ready for the Na5 counterplay.} (9... Na5 {Previously we usually went to c2, now} 10. Ba2 $5 $14 {[%cal Ra5c4,Ga2c4] I like this more, because White has spent some time. Anyway Nc4 is not possible for the moment.}) 10. Nf3 {We can develop to the natural square now.} (10. h3 {[%cal Gg1f3,Rf5g4] This is too deep, and White spent too much time for useful moves.} O-O-O 11. Nf3 h6 $132 {[%cal Rg7g5,Rg5g4] Black should be in time to organize counterplay.}) 10... Bg4 $5 $146 {The best option for Black, but position is already new.} (10... O-O-O {Almost exclusively played.} 11. Qe2 $1 {[%csl Gc4,Rd1,Ge2][%cal Rc6a5] Prophylaxis move, to remove the queen from the d-file and also guard the c4 square.} Kb8 12. O-O Bg4 {Logical idea, but White should be better.} 13. h3 $5 {Good inclusion.} Bh5 14. Rfd1 Ne7 15. Ne4 {It's a dream setup for White.} (15. Rac1 {also a good option.} Ned5 16. Ne4 $14 {Typical slight advantage.}) 15... Ned5 16. Bg5 Be7 17. Nc5 Qe8 18. Bxe7 Qxe7 19. a4 $14 {White is slightly better.}) 11. O-O Be7 $1 {The best, Black most likely is planning to go for short castle, where the king is safer.} (11... O-O-O 12. Qe2 {Transposes to 10...0-0-0.}) 12. Qc2 $5 {[%cal Ga1d1] Tricky idea, we want to develop the rook to d1, and get an improved version of the 12.Rc1 lines.} (12. Rc1 {Logical move and it could be a serious try for over the board games.} O-O {Only good move.} 13. Qd3 $5 {Creative move, to unpin the knight, it might surprise your opponents.} Bxf3 {The most logical and the best.} 14. Bc2 $1 {[%csl Gh7][%cal Rc6e5,Gd3h7] Important intermezzo, because Nxe5 was hanging as well.} (14. gxf3 $4 {Not this of course.} Nxe5 $1 $17 {[%cal Rd7d3] Using the pin.}) 14... g6 15. gxf3 {The position is interesting, not easy to play for both sides, because it's not standard structure, both sides have their pluses and minuses.} f5 $1 {The best reaction, but I am not sure many players would find it.} 16. Rcd1 Rfd8 $1 {[%cal Ge7f8] Probably the best rook to place on d8, since Black has a new plan: Bf8-Ne7.} (16... Rad8 17. f4 {The logical moves for Black are finished.} Nb8 $1 {Best move, but already very deep move.} (17... Kg7 $2 {is typical, but quite bad.} 18. Bb3 $1 $14 {[%csl Re6][%cal Gb3e6,Gd4d5] To activate the bishop. d5 is a threat, White is better.}) 18. b4 c6 $1 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gc6d5,Ge6d5] This is Black's idea, to control d5.} 19. b5 $5 {But the game goes on, and it's very unclear.} Bxa3 20. Na4 $132 {White has full compensation, and it could be unpleasant to play from the Black side.}) 17. f4 Bf8 18. d5 $5 {We must go for the forced idea:} Nxd5 19. Nxd5 exd5 20. Ba4 $5 $132 {[%cal Ra4d7] To pin the knight, position is playable for both sides.}) (12. h3 {is met with} Bxf3 $1 {Black goes for concrete line.} (12... Bh5 $2 {Bad.} 13. Rc1 O-O 14. d5 $16 {Big advantage for White.}) 13. Qxf3 Nxd4 $11 {Black is equal, maybe some accuracy is needed, but it should be okay.}) 12... Na5 $1 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Ga5c4] The only good move, to get counterplay with Nac4.} (12... Bxf3 13. gxf3 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Rc6d4,Ge3d4,Gc3b5] Taking on d4 is impossible because of c7 pawn problems.} O-O 14. Rad1 $1 $16 {[%csl Gc2,Gd1,Rd7][%cal Gd4d5] d5 is coming, and big problems could be for Black.}) 13. Ba2 Nac4 14. Qe2 {The most logical, to force the knight to capture on e3.} Nxe3 15. fxe3 {[%csl Gf1,Rf7][%cal Gf1f7] We change the pawn structure, and visually it is already much more dangerous for Black when the f-file is open.} O-O-O $1 {Black must correctly decide that short castle is dangerous.} 16. h3 {You can also not include it, but this is usually normal for White.} Bh5 17. Ne4 {[%cal Gb2b4,Ge4c5,Ga1c1] White's play is very easy.} Kb8 18. Rac1 $5 {Preparing Nc5.} (18. b4 {There is no need for b4.} f5 $1 {Good reply, probably the only.} 19. Nc5 Bxc5 20. bxc5 Nd5 $13 {Very unclear position.}) 18... Nd5 19. Nc5 Bxc5 20. Rxc5 f6 $1 {The best, to get some counterplay chances.} 21. exf6 gxf6 22. e4 {The line gets forced:} Nf4 23. Qe3 Bxf3 $1 {Only way.} 24. Rxf3 b6 $1 {Fantastic intermezzo.} (24... Qxd4 $2 {Mistake.} 25. Qxd4 Ne2+ 26. Kf2 Nxd4 27. Rxf6 $16 {White is seriously better in the endgame.}) 25. Rc2 e5 $1 26. d5 {White's position is still playable, for example:} Rhg8 27. Kh2 Rg7 {I tried some normal moves with my own brain:} 28. Bc4 $1 Rdg8 29. Bf1 $40 {[%csl Gg2][%cal Gf1g2] The attack is over, and White could be better. The line we offered is very practical, almost unknown, and Black really must show great understanding (when to castle long, when to castle short), I can assure you it's not easy for a human, and White can pose serious problems in a real game, because generally White's play is simpler.} *

