{[%evp 0,49,25,32,32,-14,42,19,16,16,20,20,46,45,40,46,50,41,50,54,23,39,49,44,74,25,78,42,55,27,86,53,81,53,68,58,62,56,42,34,42,10,55,-37,36,18,13,46,-2,-2,10,-2]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 Nf6 4. e5 Nd5 5. Bxc4 Nc6 {The topic of this chapter.} 6. Nc3 Nb6 {The only playable move.} (6... Be6 $2 {Bad move.} 7. Bb3 $1 {Important, to defend from Nxc3 threat.} Qd7 8. Nf3 $16 {[%cal Rd5b6,Gd4d5] Nb6 is impossible, otherwise it's difficult to offer a solution for Black. Just bad position.}) (6... Nxc3 $2 {Bad positional move.} 7. bxc3 $16 {[%csl Rc8,Rf8] White is strategically winning, no good way for Black to finish development.}) 7. Bb5 {To pin the knight.} Bd7 {Logical move, to defend from d5 and Bxc6.} 8. Nge2 $5 {I like this more, and it was played also by the Ex-World Champion, Ding Liren.} (8. Nf3 {I played this move two times and it was also played in the very important game Kortschnoj-Sadler, but I am not sure that it's the best.} e6 9. O-O Nb4 10. Be2 Bc6 11. a3 N4d5 {is how the aforementioned game continued.} 12. Ne4 $6 {was played by Kortschnoj, missing Black's idea.} (12. Bd3 $5 $14 {Improvement over the game, White should be slightly better.}) 12... Nf4 $1 {Nice move.} 13. Bxf4 Bxe4 $11 {Equal position.}) 8... e6 9. a3 {Useful move, as usual in this structure.} Ne7 {Normal move, it was played by Yu Yangyi against Ding in 2020.} (9... f6 $5 $146 {deserves attention, but it was never played, and it also is very risky for Black.} 10. O-O (10. exf6 {is also an option.} Qxf6 11. O-O O-O-O 12. Be3 $14 {The evaluation is good, it is a position for the future probably.}) 10... a6 11. Bd3 fxe5 {[%cal Gd4e5] White has compensation if dxe5 happens, but there is another idea:} 12. Bxh7 $5 {Beautiful move.} Rxh7 13. Qd3 {[%csl Re8] White goes for the mate.} g6 $1 {Only move.} 14. Qxg6+ Rf7 15. Bg5 Be7 {Keep in mind that White always has a repetition.} 16. f4 $5 {White can also play for a win.} (16. Qg8+ Rf8 17. Qg6+ Rf7 $11 {You can make a draw, or get extra moves to reach control.}) 16... exd4 17. Ne4 Nd5 18. N2g3 {And it really looks dangerous for Black, especially if he is not prepared.} Bxg5 19. fxg5 Qe7 20. Qh5 $5 {A lot of threats in the position now:} e5 $1 {[%csl Ge5,Rf4][%cal Rd5f4] Only move, to have Nf4 idea.} 21. Nf6+ Nxf6 22. Rxf6 Be6 {The best.} 23. Nf5 $5 {also serious option.} (23. Raf1 O-O-O 24. Rxf7 Bxf7 25. Rxf7 Qc5 $1 $11 {Position is still unclear, but Black somehow equalizes.}) 23... Bxf5 24. Rxf5 d3 $1 {Only move.} 25. Raf1 Nd8 $1 $13 {I guess Black can hold it, but it's really risky.}) 10. Bd3 Bc6 11. O-O Qd7 {Now I suggest to improve over Ding's game:} 12. Qc2 $5 $146 {[%cal Gc1e3,Ga1d1] I like this move, just finish development first, and then think about some plans.} (12. b4 {Ding's move, normal, but not the best.} a6 {And White doesn't have anymore the Qc2 idea.} 13. Qc2 Nbd5 $1 14. Be3 Nxc3 $1 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Rb2c3] Compared to our line, White doesn't have bxc3.} 15. Nxc3 Nd5 $11 {It should be fine for Black.}) 12... Nbd5 {Logical try.} 13. Be3 f5 $1 {Probably the best, to control the e4 square.} (13... Nxc3 $2 {Positional mistake.} 14. bxc3 $16 {[%cal Gc3c4] White is better of course.}) 14. Bg5 {The idea is Bxe7 somewhere, to take control of the d5 square.} Ng6 {Logical.} 15. Bc4 h6 16. Bd2 Nge7 $1 {The best, but not so easy to find it.} 17. Rfc1 g5 18. b4 a6 19. Rab1 {[%cal Ga3a4,Gb4b5] White has at least the initiative.} Kf7 20. a4 b5 $1 {Black's play is not easy.} 21. Bb3 Bg7 22. axb5 axb5 23. h4 {Sample line:} gxh4 24. Nxd5 Bxd5 25. Nf4 $14 {White's initiative is very strong. I think we found nice ideas against 5...Nc6 sideline, White has a good game in general, and honestly it is just a worse version of the lines we have seen in Chapter 6. That's why, 5...Nb6 is the main line by far.} *

