{[%evp 0,39,28,19,25,-14,35,19,32,32,16,20,78,-15,24,22,31,28,42,16,6,14,1,-38,10,1,47,36,59,52,52,13,26,13,84,55,55,0,0,3,-10,32]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 Nf6 4. e5 Nd5 5. Bxc4 Bf5 {The topic of this chapter. A very reliable line for Black, and also the one that I recommended together with GM Baadur Jobava in our course ''Ambitious QGA for Black''.} 6. Ne2 $5 {This is my main recommendation, to get a game.} (6. Qb3 {is critical, to win material, but Black is fine after} c6 7. Bxd5 (7. Qxb7 $6 {Greedy.} Nb6 $1 $36 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gf5c8] White has problems with the queen.}) 7... cxd5 8. Qxb7 Qc8 $1 {[%cal Rb7a8,Gc8c1] Black forces an endgame.} 9. Qxc8+ Bxc8 $11 {Despite being a pawn down, Black has full compensation and easy play.}) (6. Nc3 $5 {This is a good way to check your opponent's memory.} Nb4 $1 {Important move for Black.} (6... e6 $6 {The most common move, but not accurate:} 7. Bxd5 $1 exd5 8. Nge2 {White has a slightly better position, for example:} Qd7 9. O-O Nc6 10. h3 $1 $14 {[%cal Ge2g3] Useful move, against Bg4 idea.}) (6... c6 $2 {Also not good.} 7. Nge2 {[%cal Rb8c6] Black doesn't have standard development.} e6 8. O-O Be7 9. Ng3 Bg6 10. f4 $16 {[%csl Rb8] Advantage for White.}) (6... Nxc3 $2 {Positional mistake.} 7. bxc3 e6 8. Ne2 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4,Ge5] This structure is very nice for White.} Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Ng3 Bg6 11. f4 $16 {[%cal Gd1g4,Gf4f5] White has a crushing plan.}) 7. e6 $5 {We can go for this concrete idea, played only in 2 games: Cheparinov-Anton and Ohanyan-Jobava.} fxe6 {Necessary.} 8. g4 $1 {Tempo against the bishop.} Bc2 $1 {was tried by Jobava.} (8... Nc2+ $2 {was tried by Anton Guijarro.} 9. Kf1 Bg6 10. Nf3 $1 {Strong move by White.} Nc6 {If Black finishes development:} (10... Nxa1 $6 {Mistake by Anton, the game continued with 11.Bf4 and it was a complete mess, but a much more useful move was} 11. Kg2 $3 $146 {[%cal Gh1e1,Gh1d1] Important novelty, to bring the rook in the game.} Nc2 {is logical, I guess.} (11... Nc6 {Sample line:} 12. Bxe6 Bf7 13. Bxf7+ Kxf7 14. d5 Nb4 15. Qe2 Nxd5 16. Rd1 $1 $18 {[%csl Gg2] The point of Kg2.}) 12. h4 Nb4 13. h5 Bf7 14. Qb3 $16 {Huge compensation for White, also advantage.}) 11. Bf4 $1 {This is a strong move, that's why probably Cheparinov confused the moves.} N2xd4 {The best.} 12. Kg2 {Two pawns down, but very big initiative for White.} Qd7 13. Bb5 $1 {Nice move.} O-O-O {Natural, but doesn't help.} (13... Nxb5 14. Qxd7+ Kxd7 15. Nxb5 $18 {[%csl Rf8] Lost endgame for Black.}) 14. Ne5 $1 Qe8 15. Qe1 $18 {[%csl Rc6,Re8,Rf8] Too many pins, White is probaly winning.}) 9. Qe2 Qxd4 $1 $146 {The best move for Black.} (9... N8c6 $6 {[%cal Rc6d4] Black played natural move, to develop with tempo.} 10. Be3 $1 $146 {Strong improvement over the game.} Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Qxd4 12. Nf3 $1 {White develops a big initiative:} Qxg4 13. Nb5 $1 {[%csl Rc7,Rg4][%cal Re8c8,Gc4e6] A lot of threats.} Qf4 {Only move.} 14. Ne5 O-O-O 15. a3 $16 {White has a big advantage.}) 10. Nb5 Qd7 11. Nf3 {Black can equalize with precise moves.} Bd3 $1 12. Nxc7+ $1 {A lot of pieces get traded.} Qxc7 13. Bxd3 Nxd3+ 14. Qxd3 Nc6 15. O-O Rd8 16. Qe4 $44 {[%cal Gc1f4,Gf1e1] White has full compensation, so you shouldn't worry about being worse, but Black is fine. Still, I believe that this line a good weapon to have in your repertoire.}) 6... e6 7. Nbc3 Nb6 $1 {The best move for Black.} (7... c6 $6 {[%cal Rb8c6] Not great, since it blocks the development of Black's knight from b8.} 8. Ng3 Bg6 9. O-O Be7 10. f4 {White has a typical big advantage, for example:} Qd7 {To stop f5.} 11. f5 $1 {Anyways.} exf5 12. Nxd5 $146 cxd5 13. Bd3 $16 {[%cal Gd3f5] Big positional advantage.}) (7... Nb4 $6 {was good against 6.Nc3, here it is a bit slow.} 8. O-O $1 {[%csl Gg1] The obvious improvement for White.} Nc2 9. d5 $1 {Black's position is very dangerous:} (9. Ng3 $5 {Possible alternative.} Bg6 10. d5 Nxa1 11. Qe2 exd5 12. Nxd5 $36 {[%cal Gf1d1] Extremely dangerous position for Black as well.}) 9... Nxa1 10. Nd4 Bc5 11. Nxf5 exf5 12. b4 $1 {To develop with tempo.} Be7 13. Bb2 $36 {[%csl Gd5,Ge5] White has a big initiative.}) 8. Bb5+ $5 {I like this tricky check.} (8. Bb3 {is a possible way, but you transpose to big theory after} Nc6 9. Be3 Qd7 10. O-O O-O-O $132 {Transposing to chapter 6. White has a playable position, but you can expect that Black is prepared for this line.}) (8. Bd3 $6 {Bad move.} Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Nc6 $1 $132 {[%cal Gd8d7,Ge8c8] Black has absolutely no problem, and is doing very good strategically.}) 8... Nc6 $1 {This is the best move, in my opinion, and it was also played in Mamedyarov-So, Sinquefield Cup 2019.} (8... c6 $6 $146 {I really hope to see this move.} 9. Bd3 $1 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Rb8c6] And compared to 8.Bd3, this is of course what we love.} Be7 {The best for Black.} (9... Bxd3 $2 10. Qxd3 Be7 11. Qg3 $16 {[%csl Re8][%cal Gg3g7] Big problems for Black.}) 10. O-O Na6 $1 {Black must first finish queenside development.} (10... O-O $6 {Natural, but premature.} 11. Bxf5 $1 exf5 12. f4 {White plays for an attack.} Na6 13. g4 $1 {Typical idea.} fxg4 14. f5 $16 {[%cal Ge2g3,Gd1g4] White is better.}) 11. a3 $5 {Useful move against Nb4-Nd5.} (11. Bxf5 $6 {It's of course, not the same now.} exf5 12. f4 Nc7 13. g4 fxg4 14. f5 Qd7 $36 {[%cal Ge8c8] Black will castle long, that's why this attacking idea, works only with a king on g8.}) 11... Nc7 12. Re1 {We can play this position slowly.} O-O {Black is ready for short castle now.} 13. Qc2 Bxd3 14. Qxd3 Nbd5 15. Ne4 $132 {[%cal Ge2g3,Gg3h5,Gc1d2,Ga1d1] White has for sure a playable game, with space advantage. This is a rock solid position for many years.}) 9. Be3 $5 $146 {This is my recommendation, White just aims to get a game.} (9. Ng3 {is how the aforementioned game continued.} Bg6 10. h4 h5 $1 $11 {[%csl Rg3] Black has a good version of the Caro-Kann structure, the knight on g3 is not so fantastic.}) 9... Be7 {Logical move.} (9... Bb4 $5 {This is human development as well.} 10. O-O O-O 11. Ng3 Bg6 12. Qg4 {[%cal Gh2h4,Ga1d1] White has a very playable position:} Be7 $1 {[%cal Rh2h4,Ge7h4,Gc6b4,Gb4d5] The best move, stopping h4 and introducing Nb4-Nd5.} (12... Qd7 {Natural move.} 13. a4 $5 {[%csl Gb5] Prophylaxis.} (13. h4 $2 {Be careful about this trick:} Bxc3 $1 14. bxc3 Nxe5 $1 $36 {[%csl Rb5,Rg4] Qe2 is still compensation, but no need to allow it.}) 13... a6 14. Be2 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5] h4-h5 next, and it could be very unpleasant for Black.}) 13. Rad1 {Natural moves.} Nb4 14. Be2 N4d5 15. Bd2 $14 {[%eval 30,0] position, we can play it for a long time.}) (9... Qd7 $6 {The long castle plan is very dangerous of course.} 10. Rc1 O-O-O 11. Na4 $1 $40 {[%csl Rc8] Very big attack.}) 10. Ng3 {Mamedyarov's idea works better in this position.} (10. Nf4 $5 {is more solid, if you don't like 10.Ng3.} h6 $5 {Useful move.} (10... O-O $6 {Music to our ears.} 11. g4 $1 Bg6 12. h4 $1 {[%csl Rg8] Fast attack against Black's king.} Bxh4 13. Qd2 $40 {[%cal Ge1c1,Gh1h2] Easy attacking chances.}) 11. Qf3 $5 {[%cal Ga1d1,Gd4d5] Rd1-d5 is serious.} O-O {Necessary.} 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Qxc6 Qe8 $44 {Probably Black has full compensation, but it's still a game.}) 10... Bg6 11. h4 $1 {Strong now.} h5 {The most logical.} (11... Bxh4 {is met with} 12. Nh5 $1 {Key idea.} O-O 13. Nf4 Bg5 14. Nxg6 fxg6 15. Qg4 $1 {[%csl Re6,Rg5][%cal Rg4e6,Rg4g5] Double attack.} Rf5 16. Be2 $36 {[%cal Ge1c1] Long castle next, and good initiative, +0.35 according to the engine.}) 12. Nge2 $5 {[%csl Ge3,Re7] The inclusion of these two moves is in White's favor.} Bf5 (12... Bxh4 $2 13. Nf4 $18 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gf4g6] Positionally winning position.}) 13. Nf4 {h5 is under attack, so Black tries} Bg4 14. f3 Bf5 15. Rc1 $5 Bxh4+ 16. Ke2 {It looks a bit strange, but here White has the advantage, for example:} Bg5 17. g4 $1 {Strong idea, to play against the pin.} Bxf4 18. Bxf4 Bg6 19. Qd2 $36 {[%cal Ge8e7] Ke7!! is the best move, but okay show me somebody who will play it.} Qd7 20. Bg5 $14 {[%csl Re8][%cal Gg5d8] Prevent long castle, White has the advantage. You have now 2 good ways to deal with Black's tricky 5...Bf5 line, it is up to you the choice, but it's nice to have both of them in your repertoire, because depending on your opponent, you can choose when to go for the concrete line and when for the positional line.} *

