{[%evp 0,31,32,32,32,6,25,17,57,69,16,33,33,41,50,43,50,48,51,52,55,55,54,80,70,40,40,47,47,40,39,4,29,-23]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 Nc6 4. Nf3 Nf6 $5 {This sideline is sometimes played by the Italian GM Michele Godena, a great expert of QGA for Black. He used it against me in the 2015 Italian Championship, where the game finished in a draw, and he used it against GM Studer to win a nice game in the 2017 Mitropa Cup.} 5. Nc3 $1 {[%cal Gd4d5,Gf1c4]} (5. e5 $6 {I have played this move in the above mentioned game, but after} Nd5 6. Bxc4 {Black achieves a good version of the 3...Nf6 4.e5 Nd5 5.Bc4 Nc6 line (Chapter 6) because it's like White has played in that position the harmless 6.Nf3.}) 5... Bg4 $1 {Black's only continuation; otherwise, after Bxc4 or d5, White will be much better.} 6. Be3 {This is White's principled continuation because we want to see how Black intends to deal against our strong center.} e6 (6... Bxf3 $2 {Black ruins our structure and wants to continue with e5, but this idea is bad for concrete reasons:} 7. gxf3 e5 8. d5 Nb8 (8... Ne7 9. Qa4+ $1 {The killer idea.} Nd7 10. d6 $1 Nc6 (10... cxd6 11. Bxc4 $18) 11. dxc7 Qxc7 12. O-O-O $18 {[%cal Gf1h3] White's lead in development is decisive.}) 9. Rg1 $5 {[%csl Rf8,Rg7][%cal Yf8g7] Not allowing Black's bishop to move from f8.} Nbd7 10. Bxc4 {Black should play g6 if he wants to complete the development.} g6 11. Qb3 $1 Bc5 (11... Nc5 12. Bb5+ Nfd7 13. Qc2 $18) 12. Bh6 $18 {Black's position is lost.}) 7. Bxc4 Bb4 {[%csl Re4] We now need to think about the e4 pawn. It's very interesting to notice that this position can also arise from the Chigorin Opening!} 8. Qd3 $1 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gd3d4,Yf3d2] Very strong continuation. Compared to 8.Qc2, we are now defending the d4 pawn, and we will be able to play Nd2.} (8. O-O $6 Bxc3 9. bxc3 Nxe4 $15 {Not enough compensation for White.}) (8. Qc2 {Is White's most common continuation, but after} O-O 9. Rd1 (9. Nd2 $2 {Impossible because the d4 pawn is hanging.}) (9. O-O-O Bxc3 10. bxc3 Rb8 $1 $13 {[%cal Gb7b5] Black can continue with b5, and the position is very complicated.}) 9... Qe7 $13 {[%cal Ge6e5] Black prepares e5, and the position is not so clear.}) 8... O-O {This is by far Black's most common continuation.} (8... Bxf3 $2 {Once again, this move is strategically bad:} 9. gxf3 Na5 10. Rg1 $5 O-O 11. O-O-O $16 {White has a strong center and a big positional advantage. In practice, he scored the 95% of the points!}) (8... Bh5 $5 {[%cal Gh5g6] Was the move played by Godena against Studer. It's a very deep move, because Black understands that his priority is to improve the bishop on g6.} 9. O-O $1 {This simple move is our strongest continuation.} (9. Nd2 $5 {Possible, but Black's idea is} Ng4 $1 10. a3 Nxe3 11. fxe3 Ba5 $5 $13) (9. a3 $2 {Was played by Studer, but it was already a mistake:} Bxc3+ $1 10. bxc3 Bg6 11. Nd2 (11. Bg5 Bxe4 $17 {Studer-Godena, 2017.}) 11... Nxe4 $1 {very nice idea} 12. Nxe4 Qh4 $15 {[%cal Gh4e4] Black will take on e4, and is already slightly better.}) 9... O-O (9... Ng4 $2 {Doesn't make sense now:} 10. Bg5 $16) (9... Bg6 {This very logical move was played in the game Dardha-Frischmann, 2023.} 10. d5 $1 exd5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 (11... O-O 12. Rad1 $16) 12. Bxd5 O-O 13. Qb5 $1 $16 {Dardha-Fischermann, 2023.}) 10. a3 $5 {We immediately force Black to decide what he wants to do with his bishop.} Ba5 (10... Bxc3 11. bxc3 Bg6 12. Nd2 $16 {00-00 have been included, and it means that Black doesn't have the Nxe4-Nxe4-Qh4 idea because White can now play f3.}) 11. Rad1 Bxf3 12. gxf3 e5 13. Ne2 $16 {[%cal Gf3f4] f4 next.}) 9. Nd2 $1 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Rg4][%cal Gf2f3] Our key positional idea. Our center is now very well defended, and we can continue with f2-f3, making Black's bishop on g4 very passive.} a6 $5 {[%cal Gb7b5] Engine's idea is to play for a quick b7-b5.} (9... e5 {Black's most common continuation.} 10. d5 Ne7 (10... Na5 {Also possible, Black will take the bishop but will not equalize:} 11. f3 Bd7 12. a3 Nxc4 13. Nxc4 Bd6 14. Nxd6 cxd6 15. O-O $16 {[%cal Ga3a4,Ga4a5] We can put pressure on the queenside.}) 11. f3 Bd7 12. a3 Bd6 13. Ba2 $5 $14 {[%cal Gd2c4] Nc4 next, and White has a good edge. We'll now follow the game Dvirnyy-Signorelli, played in 2018, to get an extra feeling about the position.} Ng6 {[%cal Gg6f4] Black might have Nf4 ideas.} 14. g3 {was a very logical move played by Dvirnyy.} Qe7 15. Nc4 Bh3 {White has a huge advantage, and now GM Dvirnyy made the first risky decision:} 16. O-O-O {This move is not bad, according to the engine, but there is no need to sacrifice material:} (16. Rg1 $1 {Was stronger and easier: we will continue with 000 next, but we don't allow Black to play Bg2.}) 16... Rac8 {Was played in the game. Once again, 17.Rhg1 was White's simplest solution.} (16... Bg2 $1 {Black had to go for it.} 17. Rhg1 Bxf3 18. Rdf1 Bg4 19. Bg5 Bd7 $5 {White is better, but at least Black has something to hope for.}) 17. Rhg1 $1 {Then we play some other useful moves and at some point, g4 or Bg5. The engine evaluates +2,00.} (17. Bxa7 $4 {This was a very bad choice played in the game, after} b6 $1 {Black already had the initiative and ended up winning the game. From this game, we should learn that White's position is better in itself, and the most important thing is not to allow any counterplay for the opponent.})) 10. f3 $146 {Our logical continuation.} (10. a3 b5 $1 $13 {And the position is not clear at all.}) 10... b5 $1 {A strong intermezzo.} (10... Bh5 $2 {Automatic move, but bad.} 11. a3 Ba5 12. Nb3 Bb6 13. h4 $16 {Big advantage for White.}) 11. Bb3 Bh5 12. Bc2 $5 {[%csl Gd3][%cal Gc2d3] We protect our queen.} (12. a3 Bc5 $1 $13 {[%csl Rd3] Our queen on d3 is undefended.}) 12... Bg6 13. a3 Bd6 {[%cal Ge6e5] Black's idea is e5.} 14. O-O (14. Qe2 $5 {Also deserves attention.}) 14... e5 15. dxe5 Bxe5 16. Rac1 $14 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gc1c6,Gd2b3] We have a nice pressure on the 'c' file, and the c5 square is also weak.} *

