{[%evp 0,43,19,15,15,5,34,9,34,55,33,55,55,35,57,29,59,59,63,58,62,55,51,55,55,36,47,43,58,58,59,47,43,39,52,36,26,18,18,-20,14,-20,9,9,-7,-3]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 Nc6 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Yc6d4] Black challenges our center by fighting for the d4 square (or e5 square in case of d5). This variation has a very similar spirit to the Chigorin.} 4. Nf3 Bg4 {This is Black's most common continuation.} (4... Nf6 {Was analyzed in the previous chapter.}) 5. d5 Ne5 6. Bf4 {We force Ng6.} (6. Nc3 $5 {Might be another possible direction.}) 6... Ng6 7. Be3 (7. Bg3 $6 e5 $13 {[%csl Rg3] Our bishop is misplaced on g3.}) 7... e5 (7... b5 $6 {This move has been tried a few times by GMs Huschenbeth and Lubbe.} 8. a4 a6 9. axb5 axb5 10. Nc3 Rb8 {Bluebaum-Huschenbeth, 2012.} 11. Ra5 $1 $146 e6 {the critical line} (11... b4 $2 {loses immediately} 12. Qa4+ Bd7 13. Nb5 $18) 12. Rxb5 Rxb5 13. Qa4 $1 c6 14. dxc6 $1 Rb4 15. c7+ Rxa4 16. cxd8=Q+ Kxd8 17. Nxa4 $16 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gf1c4] After this spectacular sequence, we enter in an endgame where Black's pawn on c4 will fall.}) (7... Nf6 8. Nc3 e5 {trans in 7...e5.} (8... e6 $6 {Black tries to keep it independent, but after} 9. Qa4+ $1 {White is better. For example:} Qd7 10. Qxd7+ Kxd7 (10... Nxd7 11. Nd4 $1 exd5 12. h3 c5 13. Ndb5 d4 14. hxg4 O-O-O 15. Nxd4 cxd4 16. Bxd4 $16) 11. dxe6+ Bxe6 12. Rd1+ Ke8 13. Ng5 $14 {[%csl Rc4]})) 8. Bxc4 Nf6 (8... a6 $6 {Black sometimes starts with a6 if he wants to avoid Bb5+, but this is anyway not our idea, and by playing a6, Black wasted an important tempo.} 9. h3 $1 Bd7 (9... Bc8 {Against d6, but it's a very passive move:} 10. Nbd2 $5 {With the idea Bd3-Nc4.} Bd6 11. O-O Nf6 12. Bd3 O-O 13. Nc4 $16) 10. d6 $1 {We can concretely punish Black for his 8...a6.} Bxd6 11. Qd5 Qe7 12. Qxb7 $16) 9. Nc3 Bd6 {In my opinion, Black should play without a6.} (9... Nh4 $6 {Concrete move, but dubious:} 10. Bg5 $1 Nxf3+ (10... Nxg2+ $2 {loses immediately:} 11. Kf1 Bh3 12. Qa4+ $1 Qd7 13. Bb5 Nh4+ 14. Ke2 Nxf3 15. Be3 $1 $18) 11. gxf3 Bd7 12. Qb3 $1 {[%cal Gb3b7,Gd5d6] Double threat: Qxb7 and d6.} Bd6 13. Qxb7 O-O 14. Qa6 $16 {Black doesn't have enough compensation for the pawn.}) (9... a6 {by far, Black's most popular continuation. I don't know why so many players are scared of Bb5+.} 10. O-O Bd6 (10... b5 11. Bd3 Bd6 12. h3 Bd7 13. a4 $14) 11. h3 {We immediately force Black's bishop to retreat.} (11. Be2 {[%cal Gf3d2] Is White's most popular move, with the idea Nd2, but we can play more ambitiously.}) 11... Bd7 12. a4 $1 O-O 13. a5 $1 $146 {We take space on the queenside, and we have a lot of long-term plans. For example:} Nh5 {[%cal Gh5f4,Gf7f5] Black starts some kingside counterplay.} (13... Qe7 14. Re1 {Not easy to find a plan for Black.} Bc5 {Black wants to exchange the bishops.} 15. Bf1 Bxe3 16. Rxe3 Ne8 {[%cal Ge8d6]} 17. g3 {[%csl Rg6] We limit Black's knight on g6.} Nd6 18. Rc1 $16 {[%cal Gc3a4,Ga4c5,Gh3h4,Gh4h5] We can continue with Na4-Nc5, or with h4-h5.}) 14. Re1 $1 {[%cal Gc4f1] Freeing the ideal f1 square for our bishop.} Nhf4 15. Bf1 {[%cal Gg1h2,Gg2g3] We can continue with the typical "Italian" plan Kh2-g3.} f5 {looks critical} 16. exf5 Bxf5 17. Nd2 $14 {[%cal Gd2e4] Ne4 next.}) 10. h3 {Once again, we force Black's bishop to retreat.} (10. Bb5+ {a lot of players are scared of this move, but after} Bd7 11. Qb3 O-O 12. Bxd7 Qxd7 $13 {[%cal Gf6g4,Gf7f5] Black's position is fine, and he can continue with Ng4-f5.}) 10... Bd7 11. O-O O-O 12. Nd2 $1 {[%cal Gf1e1,Gc4f1,Gd2c4] We want to rotate the pieces in the following way: Re1-Bf1-Nc4.} c6 $1 $146 {This is Black's most sensible continuation.} (12... a6 $6 {I don't like a6, you already know it.} 13. a4 $14) 13. Re1 cxd5 14. exd5 $1 $14 {[%cal Gc4f1,Gd2e4,Yd2c4] We will continue with Bf1 and then Nde4 or Nc4. For example:} b5 (14... Rc8 $6 15. Qb3 $1 b6 16. Ba6 $16) 15. Bf1 a6 16. Rc1 {[%cal Gc3e4] We are preparing Nce4.} Rc8 17. Nce4 Nxe4 18. Nxe4 Bb4 $1 (18... Qe7 $6 19. Qb3 $16) 19. Rxc8 Bxc8 20. Bd2 Bxd2 21. Qxd2 f5 22. Nc5 $14 {As we have seen, the arising middlegames in the 3...Nc6 4.Nf4 Bg4 variations are always pleasant for White. Of course, Black's position is not lost, but he is not equalizing either.} *

