{[%evp 0,33,32,32,26,-10,32,0,31,43,43,43,43,75,84,99,131,131,100,63,150,83,40,41,70,71,86,94,126,115,143,108,120,97,109,88]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 b5 {The topic of this chapter. A lot of years ago, it was considered a dubious move, but nowadays, with the improvement of new engines the opinion has changed.} 4. a4 c6 5. axb5 {My recommendation. The most critical line.} (5. Nc3 {I don't see the plus to start with this move.} b4 {It's a very serious extra option.} (5... a6 6. axb5 cxb5 7. Nxb5 {Transposes to the main position.}) 6. Nb1 Ba6 $11 {Many possible lines for Black where he is fine. That's why I don't recommned starting with 5.Nc3.}) (5. b3 {is a possible line, but Black has a strong response:} e5 $1 6. dxe5 Bb4+ 7. Bd2 Bxd2+ 8. Qxd2 Qxd2+ 9. Kxd2 {Black is okay in the endgame.} cxb3 10. axb5 Ne7 $11) 5... cxb5 6. Nc3 {Black has 2 main options now:} Qb6 $5 {This line will soon overtake the move 6...a6 in popularity, the reason is clear: Black plays for 3 results.} (6... Bd7 $2 {Old line, but it's a big mistake.} 7. d5 $1 {[%csl Rb8,Rf8,Rg8] Black has serious troubles with development.} e6 {Logical, but it fails tactically.} 8. dxe6 $1 fxe6 9. Nxb5 $1 $16 {[%cal Rd7b5,Gd1h5] Huge advantage.}) (6... a6 {Most common move, but this line is in a bit of crisis now.} 7. Nxb5 axb5 {Black's idea.} 8. Rxa8 Bb7 9. Ra1 e6 $1 {[%cal Rb2b3,Gf8b4] Only move for Black, in order to have Bb4+ in case of b3.} (9... Bxe4 $2 {It's a mistake to take the pawn immediately.} 10. f3 $1 Bd5 {Logical move.} 11. b3 $1 {[%csl Rc4] And Black is not in time to defend the pawn in a satisfactory way.} Nc6 (11... e6 12. bxc4 bxc4 13. Bxc4 $18 {[%cal Rd5c4,Gd1a4] Just winning position, no compensation for the exchange.}) 12. bxc4 bxc4 13. Qa4 $16 {[%csl Rc4] Also big advantage, probably close to winning.}) 10. Ne2 $5 {[%cal Ge2c3] The safest move, plan is simple: to meet Bxe4 with Nc3.} (10. f3 {The main move, but after} f5 $1 $132 {Black gets some kind of counterplay.}) 10... Bxe4 11. Nc3 Bb4 $1 {The best move.} (11... Bc6 $6 {Main by popularity, but a bit slow.} 12. Be2 {[%cal Ge2f3] Bf3 is a serious idea.} b4 13. Nb1 Bxg2 {Black regains material, but White is fully developed now.} 14. Rg1 Bd5 15. Nd2 $16 {[%csl Rc4] Serious advantage for White, again Black has problems with the defence of the pawn.}) 12. Be2 Nf6 13. O-O Bxc3 14. bxc3 O-O {Black has compensation for the exchange, it's true, but I wouldn't say that they fully equalized, because one mistake and it could be big advantage for White. That's why we can at least say that Black's position is unpleasant. For example:} 15. Bg5 {Principled try, played in 3 games.} (15. Qd2 $5 $146 {Tricky move.} Nc6 16. Qg5 {That's the point, to improve the queen.} Bd5 17. Ba3 Re8 18. Rfe1 {Normal moves:} h6 19. Qf4 Ne4 20. Qe3 $132 {Difficult to belive that White will be worse here, it feels easier to play, but Black needs to be careful to hold the balance.}) 15... h6 16. Bxf6 Qxf6 {White has 2 options now:} 17. Ra5 $5 {is probably a better move, and it was played by Sriram against Jarmula, 2 months later after the Sargsyan game.} (17. Re1 {was played by Sargsyan.} Nc6 $1 {Important move to stop Ra5.} 18. Bxc4 Bxg2 $1 {The position is more forced:} 19. Kxg2 Qg5+ 20. Kh1 bxc4 21. Qf3 Ne7 {is how the game Sargsyan-Jarmula, Formentera 2022 continued} 22. Re5 $5 $146 {Improvement.} Qg6 23. Rg1 Qc2 $44 {The game goes on, but Black should be okay.}) 17... b4 $1 {Only move, Black is very prepared.} 18. cxb4 Nc6 19. Rc5 {Black has to decide which pawn to take:} Nxb4 {More logical move, to leave White with an isolated pawn. It was also Jarmula's choice.} (19... Nxd4 $146 {This is a novelty, but only a computer would play like this, in my opinion.} 20. Bxc4 Qg6 $1 {Only move.} (20... Rd8 $2 {seems natural, but here it's one mistake and Black can resign:} 21. Qg4 $1 $18 {Winning position, no compensation for Black.}) 21. f3 Nxf3+ $1 {Black transform the material.} 22. Rxf3 Bxf3 23. Qxf3 Qb1+ 24. Bf1 Qxb4 {[%csl Rf1,Rh2,Gh8] Without queens, this endgame should be a draw(wrong color of the promotion square for the h pawn), that's why the best try for White is to keep queens and put pressure.} 25. Rc4 Qb6+ 26. Kh1 Rd8 27. h4 $14 {With correct play, Black should make a draw, but in a real game, I think White has good chances: no human can replicate engine play, especially in such a complicated endgame.}) 20. Bxc4 $5 $146 {We can try to play this position.} (20. Rxc4 Nd5 $44 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4] In the game, Black secured quite easily the draw, the pieces are well organized.}) 20... Rd8 21. Qd2 Qxd4 22. Qxd4 {White can try to play this endgame.} Rxd4 23. Bb3 Bd5 24. Rc8+ Kh7 25. Ba4 g5 26. Rd1 Rxd1+ 27. Bxd1 $14 {Maybe an easier endgame to hold for Black than after 19...Nxd4, but it's the same situation, White can press and Black still needs to show accuracy, which could be unpleasant. Still, it is very rare to find a player who is ready to play this with Black (line only for 2 results)}) 7. Be3 $5 {My recommendation, it's a rare line (only 18 games compared to 80 in the main line), so we have chances to surprise our opponents.} (7. Nd5 {The main line.} Qb7 8. Bf4 e5 $1 {Fantastic idea, but no surprise for anybody (73 games out of 76).} 9. Bxe5 Nd7 {Theory exists here, with high level games, and the computer opinion is that this position is equal, for example:} 10. Bf4 Ngf6 11. Nc7+ Kd8 12. Nxa8 {It's how the forced line continues:} Qxe4+ 13. Ne2 Qxa8 $11 {44 games here, a lot of analysis, but everybody already knows that the evaluation is equal. (Although if you check statistics, only 9 draws happened, the rest are decisive games, so it's a fun position we can say!).}) 7... e6 8. Nh3 $5 {[%csl Gf2,Gh3][%cal Gf2f3] Good development, maybe sometimes in the future we will need to play f2-f3 (which wouldn't be possible with a knight on f3).} Nf6 9. Be2 Bb4 {The critical move, only 3 games exist here.} (9... Bb7 $2 {Very natural move, but it's bad.} 10. O-O $1 {White has a big advantage.} Bb4 11. d5 $16) 10. Bf3 O-O {was played in 2 high level games.} (10... Bb7 {was played in Fedoseev-Sychev.} 11. d5 $1 $146 {Best move, improvement over Fedoseev's game.} Qd8 $1 12. O-O Bxc3 13. bxc3 {Position is new and it's easy to go wrong here with Black.} O-O $1 {Necessary move.} (13... exd5 $4 {It's a losing mistake.} 14. e5 $1 Ne4 15. Bxe4 $1 dxe4 16. Qg4 $18 {[%csl Re8,Rg7] White has a winning advantage.}) 14. dxe6 $5 {The safest approach.} Qxd1 15. Rfxd1 Bxe4 $1 {The best.} 16. Ng5 Bxf3 17. gxf3 $5 {Interesting.} fxe6 18. Nxe6 Rc8 $1 {To stop Nc7.} 19. Nd4 $14 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Gd4b5] If Black will play like an engine, it will be a draw most likely, but in a practical game, White keeps some chances.}) 11. Ng5 $5 h6 12. h4 $1 {Very interesting idea, played in both games. If Black is not prepared, they can resign in a few moves.} Qd8 $1 {The best move, and it was played in only 1 game between 2 GMs, Laurent-Velten, 2024.} (12... Nc6 $5 $146 {Novelty, but very strange move, Black just gives up a piece.} 13. d5 Qc7 14. dxc6 e5 $1 $14 {Some crazy not human ideas, White has many moves.}) (12... Bb7 $2 {was played in the game Bluebaum-Sochacki.} 13. Qb1 $5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ge4e5] Nice idea by White, e5 is a very unpleasant move, what to do?} Nbd7 $5 $146 {The best defense probably.} (13... hxg5 $2 {was played in the game, but White got a winning position in a few moves.} 14. hxg5 Ne8 15. e5 $1 g6 16. d5 $1 $40 {[%cal Gb1e4,Ge4h4] Qe4-Qh4 next and White's attack was decisive.}) 14. e5 Bxf3 15. exf6 Nxf6 16. Nxf3 $16 {But White just won a piece. Black doesn't have enough compensation.}) 13. e5 Nd5 14. Qc2 {White's choice, natural move.} (14. Be4 $5 $146 {This is another option, and Black must find only move:} Nc6 $1 {The knight is the priority, but who will understand it?} (14... Bb7 $2 {looks good?} 15. Qc2 $1 $18 {[%csl Rg8] No, Black can resign.}) 15. Qc2 g6 $1 16. Nf3 $132 {The game continues, Black's best move is 16...Bb7, after which White has many interesting continuations.}) 14... hxg5 15. hxg5 g6 16. Qe4 {Both players were well prepared.} Re8 17. Rh6 $5 {Good preparing move.} Bxc3+ 18. bxc3 Bb7 $1 $146 {The best move, but you see, over the board it's not easy.} (18... Kf8 $2 {Finally, Black played a mistake, and it's all over.} 19. Bh5 $3 $146 {[%csl Gg6][%cal Gh5g6] Brilliant move.} gxh5 20. Rh7 $1 $18 {[%cal Gg5g6] Another quiet move, and Black's defense is collapsing. The evaluation is +7!}) 19. Kd2 {We can continue to improve.} (19. Rxg6+ $11 {If you are fine with a draw, this is always an option.}) 19... Kf8 $1 {Now, this is the best.} 20. Rh7 {To stop Ke7.} Nc6 $1 {Some magical defense by Black.} 21. Bh5 $5 {We can use our typical idea.} Nce7 {More human.} (21... Re7 $3 {Amazing move, Black must evaluate that giving up the queen is okay for Black.} 22. Bf3 Re8 $11) 22. Qf3 Nf5 23. g4 Nxc3 $1 {And Black needs to evaluate the following position:} 24. Qxb7 Qe7 25. Qxe7+ Nxe7 26. Kxc3 Nd5+ 27. Kd2 gxh5 28. gxh5 $36 {[%csl Gg5,Gh5] Engine says this is equal, okay, but questions still remain. We found interesting ideas how to pose practical questions for Black, and White isn't risking anything, you can play these lines just to test your opponents memory, and you see, one wrong move and it's all over.} *

