{[%evp 0,29,25,26,18,3,35,15,58,60,66,66,66,88,105,94,79,85,82,84,66,31,48,24,7,65,70,40,72,61,56,55]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 e6 (3... c5 4. d5 {Most likely we will transpose in 3...e6.} Nf6 5. Nc3 b5 $6 {Has been tried in some games, but it's dubious:} (5... e6 6. Bxc4 exd5 7. exd5 {we transpose in 3...e6 4.Bxc4 c5.}) 6. Bf4 $1 {Prophylactic move against b4, because in case of 6...b4, 7.Nb5! would be winning.} (6. e5 $6 {White's most common move, but here Black is fine.} b4 $1 7. exf6 bxc3 8. bxc3 exf6 9. Bxc4 Bd6 $13) 6... g5 $5 {This is probably Black's most interesting continuation, and it has been tried in only three games.} (6... Ba6 7. e5 $1 {With the inclusion of Bf4 and Ba6 this move becomes strong.} b4 8. exf6 bxc3 9. bxc3 {[%csl Ra6] The bishop on a6 is now misplaced.} exf6 (9... Nd7 10. Qa4 $1 Qb6 11. Bxc4 Bxc4 12. Qxc4 Qxf6 13. Nf3 $16) 10. d6 $1 $16 {Big difference compared to 6.e5?!}) (6... a6 $2 {Like Ba6, this move is too slow:} 7. e5 b4 8. exf6 bxc3 9. bxc3 exf6 10. Qe2+ $1 {Black cannot play Be7 because of d6, while after} (10. d6 $6 {Is not so strong now because of} Be6 $1 $13) 10... Qe7 11. Nf3 $16 {White will regain the pawn on c4 and will have a much better endgame.}) (6... Qa5 {This concrete move is refuted:} 7. a4 $1 Nxe4 8. Nge2 $1 (8. axb5 {gives Black the chances to simplify:} Nxc3 9. Rxa5 Nxd1 10. Kxd1 Nd7 $132 {is acceptable for Black.}) 8... Nd6 9. axb5 Qb6 10. Ng3 Nd7 {White has many possible continuations, but the simplest could be} 11. Bxd6 $5 exd6 12. Qe2+ $1 (12. Bxc4 $6 Ne5 $1 $13) 12... Kd8 13. Qxc4 $16 {Morozevich-Carlsen, 2009.}) 7. Bxg5 b4 8. Bxf6 exf6 9. Na4 $1 Nd7 10. Bxc4 Bd6 11. Nf3 f5 $1 {The best according to the engine.} (11... O-O 12. O-O $16 {Just much better for White.}) 12. exf5 Qe7+ $1 $146 (12... O-O $2 13. O-O $18 {Beliavsky-Bilych, 2022.}) 13. Qe2 Nb6 14. Nxb6 axb6 15. Nd2 Qxe2+ 16. Kxe2 $14 {Maybe Black can hold, but it's a very unpleasant task for a practical game.}) 4. Bxc4 c5 $1 {Black's best continuation.} (4... Bb4+ 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. e5 Nd5 7. Nge2 {trans in 4...Nf6 5.e5 Nd5 6.Nc3 Bb4.}) (4... Nf6 {Black's most popular continuation.} 5. e5 $1 Nd5 {[%csl Rc8] Compared to the 3...Nf6 variation, here Black included too early e6, which means that the bishop on c8 cannot develop to e6,f5 or g4.} 6. Nc3 c5 $1 {Black tries to create a counterplay in the center.} (6... Bb4 $6 7. Nge2 O-O 8. O-O c5 9. a3 $1 Bxc3 10. bxc3 Nc6 {We have two bishops and a better position, and we can choose between many moves. I like} 11. a4 $5 $16 {[%cal Gc1a3] With the idea of activating our bishop on a3.}) (6... Nb6 7. Bd3 Nc6 8. Nf3 $16 {[%csl Rc8] Compared to the 3...Nf6 variations, Black's bishop is now passive on c8.}) 7. Nf3 Nc6 (7... cxd4 8. Qxd4 $1 Nc6 9. Qe4 $16 {White is too active.}) 8. O-O cxd4 9. Nxd4 Nxc3 10. bxc3 Bd7 $1 {Black's only move to stay in the game.} (10... Nxe5 $2 11. Bb5+ Bd7 (11... Nd7 12. Qh5 $18 {White has a winning advantage.}) 12. Nxe6 $3 {the refutation} fxe6 13. Qh5+ g6 14. Qxe5 $18) 11. Bf4 Nxd4 (11... Be7 12. Nb5 $1 $16 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gb5d6]}) 12. cxd4 Bc6 (12... Be7 13. Qg4 $1 $16) 13. Rc1 $5 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gc1c4] We defend the bishop on c4, and after} Be7 14. Qg4 $16 {Black's Qxd4 will not attack our bishop.}) 5. d5 {White's most ambitious continuation.} (5. Nf3 {is also possible if you are fine with a small advantage in the endgame:} cxd4 6. Qxd4 Qxd4 7. Nxd4 $14) 5... Nf6 (5... exd5 $2 {bad move order because after} 6. Bxd5 $1 $16 {Black doesn't have Nf6 because of Bxf7+.}) 6. Nc3 exd5 (6... a6 7. Nf3 $1 b5 8. Bb3 c4 9. Bc2 $16 {White has a big development advantage.}) 7. exd5 $1 (7. Nxd5 {Is White's most common recapture, but after} Nxd5 8. Bxd5 Be7 $132 {The position is more or less acceptable for Black.}) 7... a6 $1 (7... Bd6 $6 {now it's very important to play} 8. Qe2+ $1 {Only after this move, White has an advantage:} Kf8 (8... Qe7 9. Nb5 $1 Qxe2+ 10. Nxe2 $18) 9. h3 $5 {Not allowing Bg4.} a6 10. a4 $16 {[%cal Gg1f3,Ge1g1] Nf3-00 next.}) 8. Nf3 ({After the automatic} 8. a4 $6 {Black is fine, because of} Bd6 9. Qe2+ Qe7 $132 {And we no longer have the Nb5 idea.}) 8... Bd6 (8... b5 $2 {looks logical, but White can play the surprising} 9. O-O $3 bxc4 10. Re1+ Be7 11. d6 $16) 9. Qe2+ $1 {As we have already seen, this is very often a key move for White.} (9. O-O O-O {is acceptable for Black.}) 9... Qe7 10. O-O Qxe2 (10... O-O 11. Qxe7 Bxe7 12. Bf4 $14) 11. Bxe2 O-O {Very important that now we are in time to play Nd2-Nc4:} 12. Nd2 $1 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gd2c4]} Be5 $1 (12... b5 $6 13. a4 $1 $16) 13. Nc4 Bxc3 14. bxc3 Nbd7 15. Ne3 $5 $14 {[%cal Gc3c4] c4 next. Black's position is not lost, but we have a long-term advantage.} *

